'''Carlos Henrique de Senna Fernandes Basto''' (27 March 1890 – 31 August 1944), also known as '''Charles Henrique de Basto''', was a Portuguese businessman and member of the Hong Kong [[Sanitary Board]].
Basto was born in [[Sé, Macau]] to José Maria de Castro e Basto and his wife, Casimira de Sena Fernandes Basto. His family was prominent among the Portuguese community in Hong Kong and Macau. He was educated in England,<ref name="1911 census">''1911 England Census''</ref> marrying Ellen Mary Cooper in London in 1912.<ref>Charles H De S F Basto ''England & Wales, Civil Registration Marriage Index, 1837-1915''</ref>
He was partner of the architect firm, Little, Adams & Wood.<ref name="juror">{{cite web|url=http://sunzi.lib.hku.hk/hkgro/view/s1927/2350.pdf|title=Jurors List for 1927}}</ref> He later quit the company, formed his own firm Blackmore, Basto & Shank, and bought his previous firm's office on the top floor of the York Building on [[Chater Road]] in 1936.<ref>{{cite web|title=Notice of Transfer|url=http://sunzi.lib.hku.hk/hkgro/view/G1936/230889.pdf}}</ref>
He was uncontested elected to the Sanitary Board in October 1932 during the period when his younger brother, the incumbent [[R. A. de Castro Basto]], left Hong Kong.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sunzi.lib.hku.hk/hkgro/view/g1932/189082.pdf|title=The Hongkong Government Gazette|date=28 October 1932|number=685|page=767}}</ref> He was nominated by Carlos Augusto de Roza and Rev. W. Walton Rogers of [[St. Andrew's Church (Kowloon)|St. Andrew's Church]]. He was also the honorary consul for Bolivia in Hong Kong.<ref>{{cite news|title=ONE NOMINATION FOR BOARD.|date=27 October 1932|page=7|newspaper=The China Mail}}</ref>
He had lived on 47 [[Granville Road]], [[Kowloon]],<ref name="juror"/> 163 [[Kowloon Tong]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sunzi.lib.hku.hk/hkgro/view/s1929/2360.pdf|title=Jurors List for 1929}}</ref> and 9 Devon Road, Kowloon Tong.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sunzi.lib.hku.hk/hkgro/view/s1936/2408.pdf|title=Jurors List for 1936}}</ref>
In 1944, Basto was a member of the [[British Army Aid Group]] in Hong Kong when he was captured and executed by the occupying Japanese.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Cooper |first1=Doug |title=A Chinese Conundrum |url=https://www.ancestry.com/mediaui-viewer/tree/48269996/person/12872411358/media/4f31c4c8-fd5e-4af6-b5be-e452366a288d?_phsrc=UbK10152&_phstart=successSource |subscription=yes|accessdate=19 June 2018}}</ref> He was buried at [[Stanley Military Cemetery]].<ref>''UK, Commonwealth War Graves, 1914-1921 and 1939-1947 for Carlos Henry Basto''</ref>
