'''Frederick M. Adamson''' was an early settler in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[Australia]]. He was the first settler to make [[botany|botanical]] collections in the [[Melbourne]] area; between 1840 and 1856, he sent to the [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew|Kew]] herbarium a series of what [[William Jackson Hooker|William Hooker]] described as "extensive and excellent collections". Several of his specimens became [[syntype]]s for ''[[Eucalyptus macrorhyncha]]''. Not much else is known about him, except that he was a member of the [[Philosophical Society of Victoria]].

