This is an incomplete list of '''unsolved known murders in the UK'''. Victims believed to have been murdered by the same perpetrator(s) are grouped together. This does not include the approximate total of 3,000 unsolved murders in Northern Ireland during [[the Troubles]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Victims condemn Northern Ireland Troubles prosecutions call|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-25021286|accessdate=6 January 2017|work=BBC News|date=20 November 2013}}</ref>
==Pre-Second World War== {| class="wikitable" |- ! width=5%| Year ! style="width:20%;"| Name of victim(s) ! style="width:15%;"| Location body found ! style="width:60%;"| Notes |- | 1536 || [[Robert Pakington]] || [[London]] || Probably the first murder with a handgun in London.<ref>{{cite book|title=The mercery of London: trade, goods and people, 1130-1578|author=Sutton, Anne F.|pages=387|publisher=Ashgate Publishing Ltd.|year=2005|isbn=978-0754653318}}</ref> |- | 1752 || [[Colin Roy Campbell of Glenure]] || [[Appin]] ||"[[Appin Murder]]". At Appin, in the west of Scotland, in the aftermath of the Jacobite Rising of 1745, inspired events in [[Robert Louis Stevenson]]'s novel ''Kidnapped''.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Appin murder investigation reveals Jacobites plotted to kill Colin Campbell Postmortem reports and modern analysis point to close-range assassination|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12482821.New_Appin_murder_investigation_reveals_Jacobites_plotted_to_kill_Colin_Campbell_Postmortem_reports_and_modern_analysis_point_to_close_range_assassination/|website=Hearld Scotland|publisher=Hearld and Times Group|accessdate=11 October 2015|date=7 August 2005}}</ref> |- |1817 ||Mary Ashford ||Sutton Coldfield ||[[Ashford v Thornton|Mary Ashford]]'s body was retrieved from a marl pit on the morning of 27 May 1817. Abraham Thornton, a local bricklayer who had been in her company, was charged with murder and rape but acquitted at a trial at Warwick on 8 August of that year, and an attempt to retry him on an appeal of murder brought by Mary's brother failed in early 1818. |- | 1857 || Emile L'Angelier || [[Glasgow]] || His lover [[Madeleine Smith]] was accused of poisoning him with [[arsenic]]. The verdict was "''[[not proven]]''".<ref>Gordon, Eleanor & Nair, Gwyneth (2009) ''Murder and morality in Victorian Britain: The Story of Madeleine Smith''. Manchester: Manchester University Press</ref> |- | 1876 || [[Charles Bravo]] || [[Balham]], London|| Known as the '''Charles Bravo Murder''' or the '''Murder at the Priory'''. Charles Bravo, a lawyer, was poisoned with [[antimony]]: he took three days to die but gave no indication of the source of the poison. No-one was ever charged for the crime.<ref>Bridges, Yseult ''How Charles Bravo Died'' Jarrolds (1956)</ref><ref>Emsley, John, ''The elements of murder: a history of poison'' Oxford University Press (2005) {{ISBN|0-19-280599-1}}. P.233</ref><ref>Jenkins, Elizabeth ''Six Criminal Women'' Sampson Low, (1949, 1951)</ref><ref>Juxon, John ''Lewis and Lewis: The Life And Times of a Victorian Solicitor'' Ticknor & Fields, (1984, 1985) {{ISBN|0-89919-277-7}}. P.115–139: Ch.12: 'The Torturer"</ref><ref>Ruddick,James ''Death at the Priory'' Atlantic Books (2002) {{ISBN|1-903809-44-4}} .</ref><ref>Williams, John ''Suddenly at the Priory'' Penguin Books (1989)</ref> |- | 1888–1902 || [[Fairy Fay]], [[Annie Millwood]], [[Emma Elizabeth Smith|Emma Smith]], [[Martha Tabram]], [[Mary Ann Nichols]], [[Annie Chapman]], [[Elizabeth Stride]], [[Catherine Eddowes]], [[Mary Jane Kelly]], [[Rose Mylett]], [[Elizabeth Jackson (1865–1889)|Elizabeth Jackson]], [[Alice McKenzie]], [[Frances Coles]] || [[Whitechapel]], London || Murders and attempted murders mentioned in connection with [[Jack the Ripper]]. |- | December 1888 || John Gill || [[Bradford]], [[West Yorkshire]] || 8-year-old John Gill's body was found in Manningham Lane in Bradford on 28 December 1888. His throat had been cut, his abdomen cut open and stabbed, his arms and legs hacked off and his ears removed. Milkman William Barrett was arrested for the murder but a Magistrate dismissed the charges. Newspapers suggested a connection to the Jack the Ripper murders, but doctors found the boy had been drugged.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eight year old Johnny Gill Murdered|url=http://www.casebook.org/press_reports/trenton_times/881231.html|website=Casebook:Jack the Ripper|accessdate=11 October 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151011112825/http://www.casebook.org/press_reports/trenton_times/881231.html|archivedate=11 October 2015|location=Wayback Machine}}</ref> |- | {{nowrap|10 February 1889}} || Louisa Smith || [[Lewisham]], London|| Prostitute Louisa Smith was found in Algernon Road, Lewisham, with a severe fractured skull caused by a blow with a blunt instrument. |- | 1902 || [[Rose Harsent]] || [[Peasenhall]], [[Suffolk]] || Known as the [[Peasenhall Murder]]. William Gardiner, a married man who was thought to be having an affair with the pregnant victim, was twice tried inconclusively and then set free.<ref>Robert Church, "Murder in East Anglia: A New Look at Notorious Cases", Robert Hale, 1987, {{ISBN|0-7090-2963-2}}, pp.&nbsp;57–75.</ref><ref>Edwin Packer, "The Peasenhall Murder", Yoxford Publications, 1980, {{ISBN|0-907265-01-4}}.</ref> |- | 1905 || [[Mary Sophia Money]] || [[Merstham]], [[Surrey]] || Body found in the [[Merstham tunnels|Merstham railway tunnel]]. The [[post-mortem]] showed a scarf had been thrust into her mouth and marks were discovered on the tunnel wall showing Miss Money had been thrown to her death from a moving train.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.truecrimelibrary.com/crime_series_show.php?series_number=11&id=1468 |title=22 September 1905 Mary Sophia Money – Merstham 22/9/1905 |publisher=Truecrimelibrary.com |date= |accessdate=21 August 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101202065355/http://truecrimelibrary.com/crime_series_show.php?series_number=11&id=1468 |archivedate=2 December 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> |- | 1907 || Emily Dimmock || [[Camden Town]], London || Known as the '''[[Camden Town Murder]]'''. Prostitute Emily Dimmock was found with her throat cut. Robert Wood was accused and acquitted after a brilliant defence by [[Edward Marshall Hall]].<ref name=marjoribanks>[[Edward Marjoribanks (Conservative politician)|Edward Marjoribanks]], ''Famous Trials of Marshall Hall'', Penguin, 1989. {{ISBN|0-14-011556-0}}</ref> |- | 1908 || [[Oscar Slater#Marion Gilchrist|Marion Gilchrist]] || [[Glasgow]] || Marion Gilchrist was an affluent 82-year-old woman who lived in the West End of Glasgow. She had been bludgeoned to death and the only thing taken was a diamond brooch. [[Oscar Slater]] was suspected as he had gone to America and had tried to pawn a brooch. He was wrongfully convicted in 1909 and this conviction was quashed in 1928: Sir [[Arthur Conan Doyle]] was prominent in securing his release.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McLaughlin|first1=Eilidh|title=BBC – Scotland – The Curious Case of Oscar Slater|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/history/the_curious_case_of_oscar_slater.shtml|website=bbc.co.uk|publisher=BBC Scotland|accessdate=6 January 2017|date=23 March 2011}}</ref> |- | 1908 || [[Caroline Luard]] || [[Ightham]], [[Kent]] || Known as the '''Seal Chart Murder'''. Mrs Luard was shot in a summerhouse in the middle of a wood near [[Sevenoaks]], Kent. Her husband was accused by some, and he later committed suicide in despair.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Davies|first1=Graham|editor1-last=Horvath|editor1-first=Miranda|editor2-last=Tong|editor2-first=Stephen|editor3-last=Bryant|editor3-first=Robin|title=Understanding criminal investigation|date=2009|publisher=Wiley|location=Malden, MA|isbn=978-0-470-72726-3|pages=xiii–xiv|edition=1|chapter=Series Preface}}</ref> Later it was suggested that murderer [[John Dickman]], hanged for a shooting on a train in 1910, was the guilty party.<ref>{{cite news|title=Heinous 1908 murder remains unsolved...or does it?|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/kent/news/heinous-1908-murder-remains-unso-a33429/|accessdate=19 February 2017|work=Kent Online|date=17 November 2007}}</ref> |- | 1909 || [[George Harry Storrs]] || [[Gorse Hall]], [[Stalybridge]] || Storrs was the owner of Gorse Hall and was a prominent business man in the town. There were suggestions that he was the lover of his friends' au pair and that she had become pregnant due to the liaison. She later committed suicide. His business interests also made many enemies for Storrs and after one attack he had a bell installed to warn police of intruders. On the night of the 1 November 1909, an intruder forced his way into the house and in the scuffle with Storrs, stabbed him 15 times. Two men were later tried independently of each other for the killing, but neither of them were convicted.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weir|first1=Kate|title=New suspect in 100-year-old murder|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/new-suspect-in-100-year-old-murder-977375|accessdate=20 February 2017|work=Manchester Evening News|date=18 April 2010}}</ref> |- | 1911 || Joseph Wilson || [[Lintz Green railway station]] || The sixty-year-old stationmaster, Joseph Wilson, was shot when returning home after closing his office at the station. Although he did not die instantly, when questioned, Wilson was unable to communicate who had shot him. Railway porter Samuel Atkinson was charged but no evidence was offered against him.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Middleton |first1=Terry |title=The Lintz Green Murder |url=http://www.bpears.org.uk/Misc/Crime/LintzGreen.html |website=bpears.org.uk |publisher=GenUKi |accessdate=11 October 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100923012036/http://bpears.org.uk/Misc/Crime/LintzGreen.html |archivedate=23 September 2010 |df= }}</ref> |- | {{nowrap|18 October 1913}} || [[Murder of Mary Speir Gunn|Mary Speir Gunn]] || Northbank Cottage, [[Portencross]], [[North Ayrshire]] || Six shots fired through a living-room window at night. The other two occupants of the room were injured, but not killed. No-one was ever charged or prosecuted for the crime. |- | 1917 || Vera Glasspool || [[Owslebury]], near [[Winchester]]||On 11 July 1917, 15 year old scullery maid, Vera Glasspool, was found in woodland close to Longwood House , where she worked. She had been strangled and stabbed. Suspicion centred on the army camp at Hazeley Down and the police offered a £50 reward for information which might lead to the arrest of the guilty party. <ref> |The unsolved murder of Vera Glasspool by Clifford Williams |2018| Hampshire Constabulary History Society| {{ISBN|978-0-9568508-2-9}} </ref> |- | 1919 || Bella Wright || Little Stretton, near [[Leicester]] || Known as the '''[[Green Bicycle Case]]''' as the victim was last seen with a man owning one. A green bicycle was found in a canal and its owner Ronald Light (1885–1975) traced. He stood trial, but was found not guilty of murder, thanks to the brilliant defence by Sir Edward Marshall Hall [[King's Counsel|KC]], who had Light in the witness box admitting to every allegation made against him, except her murder.<ref name=marjoribanks/> |-
|1920 || Florence Nightingale Shore || [[Sussex]] || Shore, the goddaughter of [[Florence Nightingale]], was found on a train at [[Bexhill, Sussex]], with serious head injuries and died four days later.<ref>{{cite news|title=Author sheds light on unsolved murder of Florence Nightingale's god-daughter|work=[[Derby Telegraph]]|location=Derby|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/Author-sheds-light-unsolved-murder-Florence/story-14133115-detail/story.html|date=14 December 2011|accessdate=8 May 2015}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Wearside Echoes: Brutal murder of Florence Nightingale's god-daughter|first=Sarah|last=Stoner|work=Sunderland Echo|location=Sunderland|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/history-nostalgia/wearside-echoes-brutal-murder-of-florence-nightingale-s-god-daughter-1-4075526||date=20 December 2011|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref> |- | 1920 || Mabel Greenwood || [[Kidwelly]], [[Carmarthenshire]] || [[Harold Greenwood (solicitor)|Harold Greenwood]] (1874–1929) was accused of poisoning his wife Mabel with arsenic. He was acquitted at [[Carmarthen]] [[Assizes]] in 1920 after a defence by Edward Marshall Hall.<ref name=marjoribanks/><ref>William Roughead, "Harold Greenwood" ''in'' "Famous Trials 4" (ed. James H. Hodge), Penguin, 1954, 13–72</ref> |- | 1931 || Evelyn Foster || [[Otterburn, Northumberland|Otterburn]], [[Northumbria]] || Foster ran a successful car hire business and on returning from one journey on 7 January 1931, picked up a 26-year-old man wearing a tweed suit, overcoat and bowler hat. He assaulted Foster, threw her into the back of the cab and then covered her with a rug which he doused with petrol and set alight. Although horrifically burned, Foster was able to crawl away from the burning vehicle and when found she was able to describe her attacker but later succumbed to her injuries the following day.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Robson|first1=Ian|title=Who killed Evelyn Foster? Author claims she may have solved 1931 murder|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/who-killed-evelyn-foster-author-13098729|accessdate=1 June 2017|work=North east Chronicle|date=27 May 2017}}</ref> |- | 1931 || [[Julia Wallace (murder victim)|Julia Wallace]] || [[Liverpool]] || Known as '''The Wallace Case'''. Julia's husband [[William Herbert Wallace]] was convicted, but this was quashed when he successfully appealed. Recent books have named a suspect. |- | 1931 || [[Murder of Vera Page|Vera Page]] || [[Notting Hill]], [[London]] || 10-year-old Vera Page's body was found in undergrowth on Addison Road in Notting Hill, London. It was believed she had been murdered elsewhere and then transported to this location. |- | 1931 || [[Hubert Chevis]] || [[Aldershot]], [[Hampshire]] || Chevis was poisoned after eating [[partridge]] laced with [[strychnine]].<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://www.open.ac.uk/Arts/history-from-police-archives/RB1/Pt2/pt2Chevis31.html | work=[[Open University]] | title=Fatal poisoning of Lieutenant Chevis|accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref> |- | 1932 ||Queenie Winifred Harman (née Hicks)|| [[St. Leonards-on-Sea]], [[Sussex]]||Aged 17, Queenie was bludgeoned to death at her home.<ref name="HarmanObs">{{cite news |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000293/19340217/259/0013 |subscription=yes |via=[[British Newspaper Archive]] |accessdate=22 April 2015 |publisher=[[Hastings & St. Leonards Observer]] |title=MAN DECAPITATED ON RAILWAY LINE |date=17 February 1934}}</ref><ref name="HarmanGaz">{{cite news |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000512/19340216/193/0020 |subscription=yes |via=[[British Newspaper Archive]] |accessdate=22 April 2015 |publisher=Exeter and Plymouth Gazette |title=ACQUITTED MAN'S SUICIDE |date=16 February 1934}}</ref><ref name="HarmanMail">{{cite news |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000324/19340213/037/0006 |subscription=yes |via=[[British Newspaper Archive]] |accessdate=22 April 2015 |publisher=[[Hull Daily Mail]] |title=DEAD ON LINE Man Acquitted of Wife Murder |date=13 February 1934}}</ref>{{Better source|reason=Ref from 1934 confirming murder and death of husband – but not suitable for calling this an "unsolved" murder over 80 years later.|date=April 2015}} Her husband, Arthurd Edward Harman, was accused but never convicted.<ref name="HarmanObs"/><ref name="HarmanGaz"/><ref name="Discharged"/> He died two years later, aged 25, after wandering onto the railway lines near Polegate.<ref name="HarmanObs"/><ref name="HarmanGaz"/><ref name="HarmanMail"/> The case for murder appears to have ended at the police court (magistrates court) level as police had no solid evidence. Mr. Harman worked for John Carter, haulier, and had been to work on the fateful day in July 1932.<ref name="Discharged">{{cite news |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000324/19340213/037/0006 |subscription=yes |via=[[British Newspaper Archive]] |accessdate=22 April 2015 |publisher=[[Hastings & St. Leonards Observer]] |title=HARMAN DISCHARGED |date=6 August 1932}}</ref> The police seemed to want the case closed rapidly and never followed any other possible leads. One interesting element was that the previous tenant at 43 Eversfield Place when vacating the flat left behind two Indian clubs (one of which was believed to have been used to kill Queenie) and a gun. He was never asked why he felt the need to have a gun whilst living in the flat.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}} There is a photograph of Queenie in the Hastings and St. Leonards Observer |- | 1934 || Unknown female || [[Brighton]] || Torso found in a trunk at Brighton Station. This is known as the '''Brighton Trunk Crime no. 1'''. ''See [[Brighton trunk murders]]''. |- | 1939 || George Stapleton || [[Greenfield, Bedfordshire|Greenfield]], Bedfordshire || Bludgeoned to death with a fence post. Stapleton, a farm worker aged 66, was attacked on Friday, 21 April 1939 while walking from Ruxox Farm along a bridleway in Greenfield to his lodgings, the White Hart Inn in [[Flitton]], and his wages stolen. The police report said the attack was maniacally brutal. [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2507&dat=19390621&id=x0VAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=kYUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4546,3207762][https://archive.is/20130627102508/http://83.222.246.143/crime_series_show.php?series_number=11&id=1313][http://content.yudu.com/Library/A1x65x/BedfordshireCountyLi/resources/8.htm]'' |}
==1 September 1939–1969== {| class="wikitable" |- ! width=5%| Year ! style="width:20%;"| Name of victim(s) ! style="width:15%;"| Location body found ! style="width:60%;"| Notes |- | 1943 ||[[Who put Bella in the Wych Elm?|Wych Elm Bella]]||[[Wychbury Hill]], [[Hagley]], [[Worcestershire]] || Skeletal remains of a woman were discovered inside a hollow tree in April 1943. Police established the victim had died approximately 18 months earlier but could not identify her. In 1944, the message "[[Who put Bella in the Wych Elm?|Who put Bella in the Wych Elm? - Hagley Wood]]" was found painted on a wall in Birmingham. Various theories about the identity of the victim and her killer have been proposed. |- | 1945 || [[Charles Walton (murder victim)|Charles Walton]] || [[Mickleton, Gloucestershire|Meon Hill]], [[Upper Quinton]], [[Warwickshire]] || On [[Valentines Day]] 1945 the body of local farm labourer Charles Walton was found murdered with his own trouncing hook and pinned to the ground with a [[pitchfork]]. The body had had a large cross engraved into the chest and neck which caused many rumours to circulate linking the murder to [[witchcraft]] or [[satanism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitedragon.org.uk/articles/charles.htm |title=Charles Walton – 50 years on |publisher=Whitedragon.org.uk |date=14 February 1945 |accessdate=21 August 2010}}</ref> |- | 1946 || [[Murder of Muriel Drinkwater|Muriel Drinkwater]] || [[Penllergaer]], [[Swansea]] || Drinkwater, a 12-year-old schoolgirl, was raped and shot in the woods in Penllergaer, Swansea. The case became known as the Little Red Riding Hood murder.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gabriel|first1=Clare|title=Mystery of 1946 murder in woods |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/7711196.stm|publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=17 September 2016 |date=5 November 2008}}</ref> |- | 1946 || [[Shooting of Margaret Cook|Margaret Cook]] || Narrow passage near [[Carnaby Street]] || Margaret was shot dead outside the Blue Lagoon nightclub. Nobody was charged with her murder at the time, but [[Scotland Yard]] detectives interviewed a suspect in 2015 after he confessed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/91yearold-confesses-to-the-murder-of-soho-sex-worker--in-1946-10393936.html|title=91-year-old confesses to the murder of Soho sex worker – in 1946|publisher=[[The Independent]]|date=16 July 2015|accessdate=12 August 2015}}</ref> |- | 1948 || Evan David Harris || Swansea Docks || Retired Industrial Chemist who was a nightwatchman at Consolidated Fisheries.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/wales_politics/8351889.stm |title= Police review 28 unsolved murders |publisher= bbc.co.uk | date=10 November 2009}}</ref> |- | 1948 || Terence McNamara || 46 Richmond Street Middlesbrough || Terence was a 22-month-old infant who was murdered in his own home whilst his mother was out at work. His father had died in 1947. The injuries sustained make sickening reading.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/news/local-news/familys-60-year-search-answers-tragic-3726116 |title= Family's 60-year search for answers |publisher= gazettelive.co.uk | date=26 November 2008}}</ref> |- | 1949 || [[Emily Armstrong]] || London || Emily Armstrong was the victim of an unsolved murder in which she had been beaten to death and later found at her place of employment, a dry cleaner's shop on St John's Wood High Street. Police later determined she had been killed roughly an hour before her body was found at around 4:00 pm. A post-mortem examination also showed that her skull had been shattered by at least 22 blows from a blunt object, later believed to be a claw hammer. |- | 1949 || Gertrude O'Leary || [[Stokes Croft]], [[Bristol]] || In the summer of 1949 the vicious murder of a well-liked, 66-year-old local licensee – Gertrude O'Leary – shocked the residents of Stokes Croft to the core. Her killer was never found.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gertlushonline.co.uk/1949-gertrude-oleary-murder.html |title=Murder of Gertrude O'Leary – Stokes Croft – 1949 |publisher=Gertlushonline.co.uk |date= |accessdate=21 August 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100709074558/http://www.gertlushonline.co.uk/1949-gertrude-oleary-murder.html |archivedate=9 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> |- | April 1954 || Olive May Bennett || [[Stratford-upon-Avon]], [[Warwickshire]] || On Saturday, 24 April 1954, Olive May Bennett, 45, was seen drinking alone in the Red Horse Hotel in Bridge Street. Shortly before midnight she was seen again, standing outside the hotel as the streets around her emptied. She had led a sheltered life until, suddenly in middle-age, she changed. She started smoking and drinking, taking endless pains with her make-up, drawing large sums of money from her Post Office bank account, and filling her address book with the names of men she was meeting. The next morning her body was found wedged against an obstruction on the banks of the [[River Avon, Warwickshire|River Avon]]. She had been strangled with a long woollen scarf and her body was weighted with a 56&nbsp;lb. tombstone wrenched from a riverside churchyard. In 1962 two women told police that on the night of the murder they were in the churchyard with two men, one of whom threatened to push them in the river and weigh them down with a tombstone. The men have never been traced.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.truecrimelibrary.com/crime_series_show.php?series_number=11&id=1320 |title=April 24th 1954 Olive May Bennett – Stratford |publisher=truecrimelibrary.com |date= |accessdate=31 October 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102120836/http://www.truecrimelibrary.com/crime_series_show.php?series_number=11&id=1320 |archivedate=2 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> |- | September 1954 || [[Murder of Jean Townsend|Jean Townsend]] || [[Ruislip]], [[Middlesex]] || On 15 September 1954, 21-year-old Jean Mary Townsend was found murdered on what was then waste land near to the junction of Victoria Road and Angus Drive.<ref>{{cite news|title=Girl found strangled near home|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000564/19540916/137/0005|accessdate=6 January 2017|work=Dundee Courier|date=16 September 1954|location=British Newspaper Archive|page=5}}{{subscription required}}</ref> The autopsy report stated that she had been strangled with her own scarf. In 1982 the Metropolitan Police announced that they were to review their files on the case following some anonymous telephone calls. To this day, no one has been charged with Jean's killing and it remains unsolved. Britain's National Archives have indicated that the police files on the case are likely to be made available for public inspection in 2031.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Olden|first1=Mark|title=Murder in Notting Hill|date=2011|publisher=Washington|location=Winchester|isbn=978-1-84694-536-6|page=179|edition=1|chapter=Notes and sources}}</ref> |- | December 1957/January 1958 || [[Murder of Anne Noblett|Anne Noblett]]{{Anchor|Anne Noblett}} || [[Whitwell, Hertfordshire|Whitwell]], [[Hertfordshire]] || On the night of 30 December 1957, 17-year-old Anne Noblett alighted a bus on the corner of Lower Luton Road and Cherry Tree Lane in [[Wheathampstead]] and began the short walk home to [[Marshalls Heath]]. A month later her partially disrobed body was found 7 miles away in Rose Grove Wood near Whitwell. Known as the "Deep Freeze Murder", mystery surrounds the circumstances over her abduction and disappearance due to the frozen condition her body was found in and the relatively mild weather at the time. Despite extensive enquiries her killer has never been caught.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.watfordobserver.co.uk/nostalgia/crimelibrary/annenoblett/ |title=The Deep Freeze Murder |publisher=watfordobserver.co.uk |date= |accessdate=27 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-42341980|title=The mystery of the 'Deep Freeze' murder|first=Phil|last=Shepka|date=17 December 2017|publisher=|accessdate=3 February 2018|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> |- | 1959&ndash;1965 || 1959: Elizabeth Figg 1963: Gwynneth Rees 1964: Hannah Tailford, Irene Lockwood, Helene Barthelemy, Mary Fleming and Margaret McGowan 1965: Bridget O'Hara || West London || '[[Jack the Stripper]]' victims. |- |1965 ||[[Murder of Elsie Frost|Elsie Frost]] || [[Wakefield]], [[West Yorkshire]] || On 9 October 1965, the body of 14-year-old Elsie Frost was found with fatal stab wounds. A subsequent investigation turned up one suspect who was later released. After this there was no further investigation and details of the case were made exempt from a Freedom of Information request. The siblings of Elsie filed an FOI request when the original exemption date was coming to an end, only to find the exemption had been extended until 2060.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://player.fm/series/ipm-share-what-you-know/ipm-04-apr-15-what-happened-to-elsie-frost |title=What happened to Elsie Frost? |website=BBC Radio 4 |date=4 April 2015 |accessdate=16 April 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150416171334/https://player.fm/series/ipm-share-what-you-know/ipm-04-apr-15-what-happened-to-elsie-frost |archivedate=16 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C6145409?hc_location=ufi|title=Murder of Elsie FROST: Metropolitan Police enquiry action file|website=[[The National Archives]]|date=2015|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref> The case was reopened in 2015 after a series of reports on BBC Radio 4. A man in his late seventies was arrested in September 2016 on suspicion of murder, more than 50 years after Elsie's death.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-37484900|title=Man, 78, held over 1965 murder of schoolgirl Elsie Frost|first=Jon|last=Manel|date=27 September 2016|publisher=|accessdate=1 October 2016|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> |- | 1966 || Helen Davidson || [[Amersham]], [[Buckinghamshire]] || On 9 November 1966, popular GP 49-year-old Dr Helen Davidson was battered to death in dense woodland in Hodgemoor Wood a few miles from her Amersham home. She had been bird-watching and exercising her dog. Her body was found the next day, but nobody has been convicted of her murder.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehistorypress.co.uk/articles/ask-the-author-monica-weller-on-investigating-a-50-year-old-cold-case/|title=Ask the author: Monica Weller on investigating a 50-year-old cold case|website=The History Press|date=2016|accessdate=28 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Real-life Miss Marple 'solves doctor's grisly 1960s murder'|url=http://www.express.co.uk/life-style/life/668108/Miss-Marple-real-life-murder-solved-1960s-Monica-Weller|first=Jon|last=Coates|date=7 May 2016|work=[[Daily Express]]|accessdate=28 September 2016}}</ref> |- | December 1966 || Mavis Hudson || [[Chesterfield]], [[Derbyshire]] || 15-year-old Mavis was last seen alive on 26 December 1966. The following day her body was found in a derelict building. She had been strangled. In spite of appeals on national TV, no arrest was ever made and the case remains unsolved.<ref>{{cite news|title=Plea to re-open murder probe|url=http://www.derbyshiretimes.co.uk/news/plea-to-re-open-murder-probe-1-489649|accessdate=24 April 2017|work=Derbyshire Times|date=12 November 2009|language=en}}</ref> |- | January 1967 || [[Murder of Bernard Oliver|Bernard Oliver]] || [[Tattingstone]], [[Ipswich]], [[Suffolk]] || Bernard Oliver, 17, disappeared on 6 January 1967 and his dismembered body was found in suitcases near to Tattingstone, Ipswich 10 days later. No-one has been charged over his murder but Suffolk Police stated in January 2017 that DNA evidence may help to yield some clues 50 years on.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tattingstone suitcase murder: Police appeal over Bernard Oliver death|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-suffolk-38527821|accessdate=6 January 2017|work=BBC News|date=6 January 2017}}</ref> |- | 1967 || Herbert Wilkinson || [[Middlewich]], [[Cheshire]] || In October 1967, the body of a solicitor was discovered in a shallow grave by the side of the Trent & Mersey Canal. 54-year-old Herbert Wilkinson, a lonely bachelor, allegedly with homosexual tendencies, who, seven months earlier, had been struck off by the Law Society because of problems with his practice in Middlewich.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cc-publishing.co.uk/Archives/wilkinson.html |title=Cheshire Magazine |publisher=Cc-publishing.co.uk |date=2 June 1967 |accessdate=21 August 2010}}</ref> |- | November 1967 || [[Murder of Rita Ellis|Rita Ellis]] || [[RAF Halton]], [[Buckinghamshire]] || On 12 November 1967, the body of Rita Ellis was found partially hidden under leaves and foliage at Rowborough Copse, part of the RAF Halton Estate. Ellis, who was in the [[Women's Royal Air Force|WRAF]] and worked in the catering department of the [[RAF Hospital|RAF hospital]] on the camp, had been beaten, sexually assaulted and strangled. She was last seen on the previous evening (11 November). The case was re-opened in 2017 for a second time, although new DNA techniques have meant that the police now have a DNA profile of the killer.<ref>{{cite news|title=New DNA clue in 1967 RAF base murder|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-41927357|accessdate=7 December 2017|work=BBC News|date=9 November 2017}}</ref> |- | 1968&ndash;1969 || Patricia Docker, Jemima McDonald & Helen Puttock || Glasgow || "[[Bible John]]" victims. |- | 1969 || Annie Walker || [[Heather, Leicestershire]] || Beaten to death in her home. By re-examining evidence gathered at the scene, police have now been able to extract [[DNA profiling|DNA samples]] which would positively identify the murderer, but have yet to find a match for the killer's DNA profile.<ref>{{cite web|first=Tom |last=Royce |url=http://www.therealestatebloggers.com/2006/07/24/sarah-anne-walker-charges-upgraded-to-capital-murder/ |title=Sarah Anne Walker Charges Upgraded to Capital Murder |publisher=Therealestatebloggers.com |date= |accessdate=21 August 2010}}</ref> |-
