==1970s== {| class="wikitable" |- ! width=5%| Year ! style="width:20%;"| Name of victim(s) ! style="width:15%;"| Location body found ! style="width:60%;"| Notes |- | 8 March 1970 || Jacqueline Ansell-Lamb || [[Mere, Cheshire]] || An 18-year-old last seen hitch-hiking from London to [[Greater Manchester|Manchester]]. Her body was discovered six days later by a farmer in Square Wood, near [[Knutsford]]. She had been [[Sexual assault|sexually assaulted]] and [[strangulation|strangled]] to death with an electrical cord.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cheshiremagazine.com/Archives/lamb.html |title=Cheshire Magazine |publisher=Cheshire Magazine |date=8 March 1970 |accessdate=21 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/serial-killer-who-stalked-young-14618227 |title=Did a Serial Killer Murder Jacci Ansell-Lamb |publisher=Manchester Evening News |date=7 May 2018 |accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref> |- | 10 March 1970 || Susan Long || [[Aylsham]], Norfolk || The Norwich Union worker had been out dancing at the Gala Ballroom in Norwich and caught the last bus home to Aylsham. She arrived at around 11:10{{nbsp}}pm and began the seven-minute walk to her parents' home, but never arrived. The headlights of a milk-float picked the shape of her body lying in a pool of rainwater in a lovers' lane the following morning.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/norfolk/3477377.stm | work=BBC News | title=DNA breakthrough over 1970 murder | date=10 February 2004 | accessdate=11 May 2010}}</ref> |- | 31 March 1970 || Philip Green || [[Shirehampton]], [[Bristol]] || 11-year-old Philip Green left his home in [[Sea Mills, Bristol|Sea Mills]] to collect golf balls on the nearby Shirehampton golf course. The following day his battered body was found in a wooded area of the course. The case remains unsolved despite one of the biggest police inquiries in the Bristol area, which was assisted by Scotland Yard. In 2010 on the 40th anniversary of his murder, [[Avon and Somerset Constabulary]] announced a new forensic investigation of the case that would use [[DNA profiling]].<ref>{{cite news| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/bristol/8579024.stm | work=BBC News | title= New appeal over 1970 murder of boy in Bristol | date=31 March 2010 | accessdate=3 May 2012}}</ref> |- | October 1970 || Barbara Mayo || [[Ault Hucknall]] near [[Bolsover]], [[Derbyshire]] || In October 1970, Barbara Mayo set off from her London home to hitchhike north. Six days later the 24-year-old's body was found in a wood by the north-bound carriageway in view of Hardwick Hall. The teacher had been raped and then strangled. Twenty years later, in 1990, detectives were able to confirm using DNA that Mayo's killer was the same man who had raped and strangled 18-year-old Jacqueline Ansell-Lamb seven months previously.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisisnottingham.co.uk/news/Unsolved-murder-book-probes-new-link-Barbara-Mayo-killing/article-531503-detail/article.html |title=Murder of Barbara Mayo link to M6 killing |publisher=Thisisnottingham.co.uk |date= |accessdate=21 August 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100709202814/http://www.thisisnottingham.co.uk/news/Unsolved-murder-book-probes-new-link-Barbara-Mayo-killing/article-531503-detail/article.html |archivedate=9 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> |- | March 1971 ||{{Anchor|Burton John Doe}}Fred the Head ||[[Burton on Trent]], [[Staffordshire]] || A policeman found bone fragments near to the [[River Trent]] in Burton in March 1971. These fragments were unearthed and in the process revealed a man who was in a kneeling position with his hands tied and wearing pink socks. The only personal effect on him was his wedding ring. In 2017, a DNA analysis led police to believe it could be John Henry Jones from [[Trevor, Wrexham|Trevor]], near [[Wrexham]] in [[North Wales]] who had gone missing in 1970. This proved to be incorrect, and neither case has been solved.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kreft|first1=Helen|title=Fred the Head murder detectives make breakthrough after 46 years|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/local-news/fred-head-murder-cops-baffled-142217|accessdate=24 July 2017|work=The Derby Telegraph|date=27 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-40709489|title=Mystery murder man not John Henry Jones of Llangollen, DNA shows|work=BBC News|date=24 July 2017|access-date=24 July 2017}}</ref> |- | May 1971 || Rose Lifely || [[Bournemouth]], [[Hampshire]] || Miss Rose Lifely was 73-years-old when she was stabbed to death in her Northcote Road home between 15 and 17 May 1971, the victim of a "maniacal attack", according to police. Police believed the killer lived in the local area, broke into her home to steal and repeatedly stabbed her when she confronted him. On 25 May, the Evening Times reported that police were hunting for a "cuddly" buxom 18-year-old blonde and two youths, who had gone to second-hand shops in Bournemouth attempting to sell jewellery similar to pieces missing from Lifely's home.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=6-dAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Y6cMAAAAIBAJ&pg=2646,3818308&dq=lifely | work=Evening Times | title=Police hunt for "cuddly" blonde | accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.bournemouthecho.co.uk/news/11620942.Couple_researching_family_tree_discover_details_of_grisly_unsolved_murder/#comments-anchor | work=Bournemouth Echo | title=Ancestry researchers saddened by details of Rose Lifely's violent death | accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref> |- | June 1971 || Gloria Booth || Ruislip, Middlesex || On the morning of Sunday 13 June, the naked body of Gloria Booth was discovered on a recreation ground off Nairn Road, approximately half a mile from South Ruislip Underground Station and a mile from the scene of the Jean Townsend killing 17 years earlier. Like Jean Townsend, Mrs Booth – a 29-year-old housewife from Ealing – had died from strangulation and it appeared that – as in the Townsend killing – a scarf had been used.<ref>"Police search for clues in murder hunt", Middlesex County Times and Gazette, 18 June 1971.</ref> |- | June 1972 || [[Judith Roberts (murder victim)|Judith Roberts]] || [[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]], Staffordshire || A 14-year-old girl was battered to death not far from her family home in Tamworth. A young soldier stationed at Whittington Barracks confessed to the murder and served 25 years in jail. However, he later claimed that his confession was a result of psychological problems he was experiencing at the time; there being no other evidence against him, his conviction was overturned by the Court of Appeal. The real killer remains unknown.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/36649.stm | work=BBC News | title=Murder conviction quashed after 25 years | accessdate=11 May 2010}}</ref> |- | November 1972 || Amala Ruth De Vere Whelan || [[Maida Vale]], London || On 12 November 1972, a 22-year-old woman was found dead at her home in Randolph Avenue, Maida Vale, west London. She had been beaten, raped, and strangled, but the subsequent investigation failed to link any suspect to the crime. In January 2017, police issued a fresh appeal for information.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Grafton-Green|first1=Patrick|title=Fresh appeal over brutal 1972 'ripper' murder of Maida Vale woman strangled with a stocking|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/crime/maida-vale-murder-fresh-appeal-after-woman-brutally-beaten-raped-and-strangled-a3432896.html|accessdate=5 January 2017|work=Evening Standard|date=5 January 2017}}</ref> |- | September 1973 || [[Stephen Downing case|Wendy Sewell]] || [[Bakewell]], Derbyshire || A 32-year-old legal secretary was savagely beaten in a churchyard, and later died of her wounds. The church groundskeeper [[Stephen Downing case#Stephen Downing|Stephen Downing]] was convicted and served 27 years for the murder, but the verdict was eventually overturned on [[Court of Appeal|appeal]]. The case was re-investigated by police, but no further arrests were made.<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC – Press Office – In Denial of Murder background|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2004/02_february/12/denial_murder_mckay.shtml|accessdate=6 January 2017|work=www.bbc.co.uk|date=29 October 2014}}</ref> |- | 1974 || Glenis Carruthers || [[Clifton, Bristol]] ||A 20-year-old woman from [[Amersham]] was found strangled on [[Clifton Down]] after she had left a friend's 21st birthday on Friday 18 January at 10{{nbsp}}pm.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2010/12/31/jo-yeates-murder-bears-similarities-to-unsolved-strangling-nearby-from-1974-115875-22816596/|title=Jo Yeates murder bears similarities to unsolved strangling nearby from 1974 – mirror.co.uk|website=mirror.co.uk|accessdate=31 December 2010}}</ref> |- | 1974 || {{anchor|Cockley Cley Jane Doe}} [[Norfolk headless body]] || [[Cockley Cley]], Norfolk || Concealed in weeds off the Cockley Cley road, near Swaffham, the badly decomposed and headless body of a young woman was found by a farm worker. She was wearing a pink, frilled Marks & Spencer nightdress, but a better clue was the brown plastic sheet in which she was wrapped, bearing the letters NCR (National Cash Register). Only six such sheets were made by a Scottish company between 1962 and 1968, but police never identified the woman, let alone her killer. Today, there is no grave or headstone, just an unmarked spot in a Swaffham churchyard.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.lynnnews.co.uk/news/Cockley-Cley-Murder-hunt-draws.4098649.jp |title=Cockley Cley: Murder hunt draws a blank – News |publisher=Lynn News |date=20 May 2008 |accessdate=21 August 2010}}</ref> |- | 1975 || [[Eve Stratford]] || [[Leyton]], London|| Stratford was found dead on 18 March 1975. The [[Bunny girl]] who worked at the [[Playboy Club]] in [[Park Lane (road)|Park Lane]] where she had been pictured with [[Eric Morecambe]] and [[Sid James]], had her throat cut between eight and 12 times. She had also been tied up and gagged and was found by her boyfriend lying on the floor in her apartment in Lyndhurst Drive, Leyton, London. In 2007, police found links between Stratford's murder and that of 16-year-old [[Lynne Weedon]]. Weedon had been beaten over the head with a blunt object as she took a short-cut to her home in [[Hounslow]] six months after Stratford's death. Despite horrific injuries Weedon was alive when found the next morning but died a week later in hospital without regaining consciousness. Both cases were featured on the [[BBC]] [[Crimewatch]] programme in September 2007, where, thanks to new [[DNA]] techniques, it was said they were sexually motivated and were committed by the same person.<ref>{{cite news|title=Case of murdered model reopens|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/london/content/articles/2007/10/04/walthamforest_eve_video_feature.shtml|accessdate=6 January 2017|work=BBC news|date=4 October 2007|language=en-gb}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bunny Girl And Teen Murders: Appeal 40 Years On|url=http://news.sky.com/story/bunny-girl-and-teen-murders-appeal-40-years-on-10347560|accessdate=6 January 2017|work=Sky News|date=3 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Silent witness: Police find DNA link in murders of school pupil and Bunny girl|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-483774/Silent-witness-Police-DNA-link-murders-school-pupil-Bunny-girl.html|accessdate=6 January 2017|work=Mail Online|date=25 September 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Menhinnitt|first1=Dan|title=DNA evidence links murders after 32 years|url=http://www.thisislocallondon.co.uk/news/topstories/display.var.1712630.0.dna_evidence_links_murders_after_32_years.php|accessdate=6 January 2017|work=This Is Local London|date=25 September 2007}}</ref> |- | 1976 || [[Renee MacRae|Renee and Andrew MacRae]] || Dalmagarry, [[Highland (council area)|Highland]] || Described as one of the most baffling mysteries in Scottish criminal history, the murder of Renee MacRae and her three-year-old son Andrew, shocked and scandalised the Highlands, and it mesmerised the small, tight-knit community in Inverness.<ref>Miller, Russell. [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/article386582.ece "Searching high and low"], ''[[The Times]]''. 8 May 2005.</ref> MacRae had planned to spend the weekend in Perthshire with her lover, a married man who was also Andrew's father. On the evening of Friday, 12 November 1976, MacRae left Inverness and headed south on the A9. At ten o'clock that evening a train driver reported a car ablaze on a lay-by adjacent to the A9 trunk road at Dalmagarry. The bodies have never been found, though traces of blood matching Renee and Andrew's blood type were discovered in the boot of the burnt out car. Attention focused on the nearby Dalmagarry quarry, where a senior member of the police believed they were buried. A 2004 excavation of the area found nothing of interest, however a local farmer has opined that the bodies could be buried under the A9, which was in the middle of a major programme of upgrading at the time of the disappearance. The farmer called for the road to be excavated at the spot where a radar survey he commissioned found "anomalies".<ref>Roass, David. [http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/home-news/dig-up-past-plea-to-solve-34-year-mystery-of-renee-macrae-s-death-1.1006805 "Dig up past plea to solve 34-year mystery of Renee MacRae's death"]. ''[[Herald Scotland]]''. 15 February 2010</ref> |- | 1978 || [[Georgi Markov]] || London || Agents of the Bulgarian secret police, Darzhavna Sigurnost, assisted by the KGB had previously made two failed attempts to kill Markov before a third attempt succeeded. On 7 September 1978, Markov walked across Waterloo Bridge spanning the River Thames, and was waiting at a bus stop on the other side, when he was jabbed in the calf by a man holding an umbrella. The man apologized and walked away. Markov would later tell doctors that the man had spoken with a foreign accent. The event is recalled as the "Umbrella Murder" with the assassin claimed to be Francesco Gullino, codenamed "Piccadilly". |- | 1978 || [[Carl Bridgewater]] || Yew Tree Farm, [[Kinver]], Staffordshire || 13-year-old Carl Bridgewater was shot in the head at close range when he disturbed burglars while delivering a newspaper to a house on 19 September 1978. The [[Bridgewater Four]] were originally convicted in 1979, but were acquitted in 1997.<ref>{{cite web|title=20 September 1978: Police hunt Bridgewater killers|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/september/20/newsid_2524000/2524697.stm|website=BBC On this Day|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=8 October 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151008133854/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/september/20/newsid_2524000/2524697.stm|archivedate=8 October 2015|location=Wayback Machine|date=20 September 1978}}</ref> |- | 1978 || Walter Taylor || Ashby [[North Lincolnshire]] || Taylor, 17, was found dead shortly before Christmas on Jubilee Playing Fields, Ashby. He had been attacked with a piece of wood.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-humber-19266812|title=BBC News – Sister's 'cold case' hope over brother's murder in 1978|website=BBC News|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> |- | 1979 || Lynda Farrow || Whitehall Road, Woodford Green, [[London]] || On 19 January 1979, heavily [[pregnant]] mother of two Lynda Farrow was found brutally murdered in her home in Whitehall Road. Her throat had been slashed and she had been raped. Earlier that day, Farrow had been shopping with her mother, and had bought a new pair of shoes and a coat. She then went to her partner's fruit stall before returning home by car. It is believed that Farrow either ran into her home to answer her ringing phone, leaving the door open behind her, or that she knew her attacker and let him in willingly. Farrow's body was found by her two daughters. In 2010, Farrow's killing was reconstructed on BBC's [[Crimewatch]]. The appeal featured her partner, now remarried, and her two daughters. The only sighting of Farrow's killer was by her neighbour, who saw a man wearing a long black coat entering Farrow's home at around 2{{nbsp}}pm. He had blonde hair and blue eyes. The only other clue to the killer is a set of footprints leading to Farrow's house. So far, nobody has been convicted for her murder.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian-series.co.uk/news/rbnews/4080569.WOODFORD_GRN__Farrow_murder___daughter_speaks_of_horrific_discovery/|title=WOODFORD GRN: Farrow murder – daughter speaks of horrific discovery|author=Daniel Binns|website=East London and West Essex Guardian Series|accessdate=20 December 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220203508/http://www.guardian-series.co.uk/news/rbnews/4080569.WOODFORD_GRN__Farrow_murder___daughter_speaks_of_horrific_discovery/|archivedate=20 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/7851695.stm | work=BBC News | title=Mother in appeal over 1979 murder | date=27 January 2009}}</ref> |- | 17 April 1979 || Gordon Snowden || [[Sutton Bridge]], South Lincolnshire || At around 2am (after Easter Monday), Gordon Snowden, 60, a petrol pump attendant at Sutton Bridge Motors, located on Bridge Road near [[Crosskeys Bridge]], was found lying beside his kiosk with severe head injuries. A [[Cash register|cash till]] had been stolen. Snowden later died in hospital from his injuries. Part of the investigation centred on trying to trace a [[Citroën 2CV]] seen on the garage forecourt shortly before the murder. The [[cold case]] remains one of [[Lincolnshire Police]]' few unsolved murders.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk/news/lincoln-news/four-mysterious-murders-remain-unsolved-69777|title=Four mysterious murders that remain unsolved|work=LincolnshireLive|date=9 April 2017|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref><ref name="LCN1">{{cite news|url=https://thelincolnite.co.uk/2015/03/lincolnshires-unsolved-murder-cases-span-36-years/|title=Lincolnshire's unsolved murder cases span 36 years|work=the LINCOLNITE|date=31 March 2015|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> In the late 1990s, British serial contract killer/hitman [[John Childs (murderer)|John "Bruce" Childs]] from East London,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/psycho-serial-killer-dubbed-narcissistic-7703676|title=Psycho serial killer dubbed narcissistic told he will die behind bars|work=Mirror|date=6 April 2016|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> convicted of six killings in the 1970s, confessed to five more murders from his jail cell.<ref name="TLES1">{{cite news|url=|title=Serial killer admits five more murders|work=The London Evening Standard - Patrick Mcgowan|date=17 November 1998}}</ref><ref name="TFL">{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/The+only+way+to+make+Childs+laugh+is+start+talking+about+killing...-a060627740|title=The only way to make Childs laugh is start talking about killing people|last=Edwards|first=Jeff|date=17 November 1998|work=The Mirror|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> His claimed a fifth victim was Snowden.<ref name="TLES1" /><ref name="TFL" /> Childs said he killed Snowden with a cosh because he was afraid he would be recognised after dumping another murder victim's car nearby in the River Nene. Six months earlier, Childs claimed he and associate Henry (Harry) "Big H" Mackenney<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/oct/31/ukcrime.hughmuir|title=Murder case pair convicted on word of liar are cleared|work=The Guardian|date=31 October 2003|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/give-whole-lifers-suicide-option-6946349.html|title=Give whole lifers suicide option|website=Evening Standard|date=14 January 2004|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> had called at the filling station after murdering Ronald Andrews<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.alamy.com/stock-photo-crime-lambeth-magistrates-court-henry-big-h-mackenney-london-107980159.html|title=Crime - Lambeth Magistrates' Court - Henry "Big H" Mackenney - London|work=PA Images|date=4 October 1979|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> and dumping his car in the nearby River Nene. Fearing that Snowden would remember the two strangers after the car was recovered, Childs went back to secure his silence. He said: "I battered him to death with a cosh in his office and took the till to make it look like robbery. He was an old boy, and when I look back I'm sorry. But in those days I was ruthless about eliminating risks. "It may sound silly, but I'm telling this now because I think that man might have relatives and I would like them to know the truth."<ref name="TLES1" /><ref name="TFL" /> However, Lincolnshire Police have confirmed that nobody has ever been charged or prosecuted in relation to the murder.<ref name="LCN1" /> |- | 1979 || [[Bedgebury Forest Woman]] || [[Bedgebury Forest]], [[Kent]] || On 23 October 1979, a mystery woman aged between 30 and 35 was found in Bedgebury Forest having been beaten to death. The discovery led to a murder enquiry but she was never identified. It was thought she had come from Eastern Europe and had one child. She was white, about 5&nbsp;ft 1 in, of thin build, with brown eyes and dark brown, shoulder-length straight hair. When found she was wearing black shoes, a floral dress and a black polo neck jumper. Police had re-investigated the case in 1999, and in May 2000 Harry Pennells from East Sussex stood trial for her murder but was acquitted after a four-week trial.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/778172.stm|work=BBC News|title=Driver not guilty of hitcher murder|date=5 June 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/7056796.stm|work=BBC News|title=New appeal over 1979 forest death|date=22 October 2007}}</ref> |}
== 1980s ==
{| class="wikitable" |- ! width=5%| Year ! style="width:20%;"| Name of victim(s) ! style="width:15%;"| Location body found ! style="width:60%;"| Notes |- | c.15 May 1980 || Jessie Earl || [[Eastbourne]] || Aged 22, disappeared around 15 May 1980. Her skeletal remains were found 9 years later in April 1989 in bushes at Beachy Head. British Serial Killer [[Peter Tobin]] is now considered an official suspect in Earl's murder, as he lived in Eastbourne in the early 1980s. Police later commented, however, that they "cannot prove anything unless Tobin confesses".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/2008/12/07/parents-of-murdered-student-jessie-earl-hope-end-may-be-in-sight-after-28-year-hunt-for-her-killer-78057-20952144/ |title=Parents of murdered student Jessie Earl hope end may be in sight after 28 year hunt for her killer |publisher=The Daily Record |date= |accessdate=21 August 2010}}</ref> |- | 1981 || [[Nude in the Nettles]] ||[[Yorkshire]] || A woman's naked and decomposed body was found dumped in bushes next to a country road near [[Sutton Bank]] on 28 August 1981 after police received an anonymous tip off from a "well spoken man" who refused to give his name for "national security reasons". |- | 1982 || [[Roberto Calvi]] || [[Blackfriars Bridge]] || Italian banker, chairman of [[Banco Ambrosiano]] which collapsed in one of modern Italy's biggest political scandals, found hanged. The death was ruled as murder after two coroners' inquests and an independent investigation. In June 2007, five people were acquitted of his murder after a trial in Rome. See also "[[In God's Name]]", a book by [[David Yallop]], which relates Calvi's murder, and the 'suiciding' of his secretary, to corruption and possibly the death of [[Pope John Paul I]] – Papa Albini. |- | 14 August 1982 || Gurcharn Singh Landa (known as 'John') || Cyprus Road, [[Mapperley]], [[Nottingham]] || The 33-year-old Nottingham taxi driver was found dead in the early hours of Saturday 14 August 1982, having been stabbed 87 times. The police believe he was robbed of his takings and then stabbed, mostly in the chest. 11 people were arrested but no one charged. The father of eight was sent to Peel Street at about 4{{nbsp}}am to pick up a passenger called 'Shelton,' who had rung from a phone box. Police believe he picked someone up before driving to Cyprus Road, about a mile away. At 4:05{{nbsp}}am, a woman living on Cyprus Road heard a car brake suddenly and looking out of the window, saw the taxi rocking violently as though a fight was taking place. She also reported seeing a man searching the taxi's dashboard. She called the police then went to help but Mr Landa died shortly after police arrived. The police re-opened the case in August 2012.<ref name = "BBC 14-08-2012">{{cite news |title=Bid to solve 1982 Gurcharn Singh Landa taxi driver murder |publisher=BBC |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-nottinghamshire-19200976 |date= 14 August 2012|accessdate=14 August 2012 |work=BBC News}}</ref> |- | 1983 || Janice Carole Weston || [[Cambridgeshire]] || At 0900 hrs on Sunday, 11 September 1983, the fully clothed body of an unidentified female was found in a ditch adjacent to a lay-by on the northbound carriageway of the A1 road, approximately 1{{fraction|1|2}} miles south of the Brampton Hut roundabout, Cambridgeshire. The body was identified as that of Janice Weston formerly living in London, a solicitor and partner of a well established firm in Lincolns Inn, London. She was last seen alive on the previous day, at her office in London.<ref name="CambsPolicePUB0211">{{Citation|title=FOI request|url=http://www.cambs.police.uk/about/foi/disclosure/PUB0211-2009.pdf|publisher=[[Cambridgeshire Constabulary]]|access-date=22 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717022555/http://www.cambs.police.uk/about/foi/disclosure/PUB0211-2009.pdf|archive-date=17 July 2011|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref> |- | 17 April 1984 || [[Murder of Yvonne Fletcher|WPC Yvonne Fletcher]] || Outside the Libyan Embassy, London || WPC Yvonne Fletcher was patrolling the area just outside the Libyan embassy during a protest when shots were fired into the crowd killing her, and injuring 10 others. The official inquest into her death ruled that she was killed by automatic weapon fire from within the Embassy. After much tension, all staff were returned to their home country. The Libyan government accepted responsibility in 1999, but no one has ever been prosecuted for her death.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1568135/Female-officers-injured-in-the-line-of-duty.html |title=Female officers injured in the line of duty |first= |last= |website= |accessdate=27 September 2015}}</ref> |- | 1 June 1984 || [[Murder of Mark Tildesley|Mark Tildesley]] || No body found || Seven-year-old Mark Tildesley disappeared while visiting a funfair in [[Wokingham]], [[Berkshire]] on the evening of 1 June 1984. He was lured away from the fair and his bicycle was found chained to railings nearby.<ref name=BBC570385>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/570385.stm|title=Cooke: The predatory paedophile|website=[[BBC News]]|date=17 December 1999|accessdate=22 April 2015}}</ref> In 1991 it emerged that Mark had been abducted, drugged, tortured, raped and murdered by [[Sidney Cooke#"Dirty Dozen"|a London-based homosexual paedophile gang]] on the night he disappeared.<ref name=BBC570385/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/paedophile-gets-life-for-killing-boy-7-at-orgy-homosexual-ring-abducted-children-and-drugged-them-for-group-sex-1559081.html|title=Paedophile gets life for killing boy, 7, at orgy: Homosexual ring abducted children and drugged them for group sex |publisher=[[The Independent]]|date=23 October 1992|accessdate=30 January 2013}}</ref> |- | 8 December 1984 || Lisa Hession || [[Leigh, Greater Manchester|Leigh]], [[Greater Manchester]] || 14-year-old Lisa Hession was attacked, sexually assaulted and strangled to death on Saturday 8 December 1984, as she walked home alone from a party. Her body was discovered just before midnight in Rugby Road, Leigh, 200 yards from the family home. Her mother, Christine, reported her missing when she failed to return home, but within a very short space of time, she received a call from the police to make her way to Leigh Infirmary and identify her daughter's body. Hession's clothing had been disturbed (suggesting a sexual motive), and she also had marks around her neck and a black eye. The case went cold, but advances in DNA technology allowed the swabbing of men in the Leigh and Wigan area to take place in 2011. However, nobody has been charged with the murder. Hession's mother died in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leighjournal.co.uk/news/11644523.30_years_on_and_still_no_justice_for_murdered_schoolgirl/|title=30 years on and still no justice for murdered schoolgirl|website=leighjournal.co.uk|accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref> |- | 9 December 1984 || Peter Miller || [[Great Yarmouth]], [[Norfolk]] || The 24-year-old was found stabbed in his kitchen by his brother. He died of one single stab wound to the chest. Although he had links to convicted criminals Andrew Hall and James Ventham, his murder was not linked to either of them. A CS canister was also found at the scene, believed to have been used by either Miller or his killer during a struggle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.norfolk.police.uk/newsevents/coldcases/homicideattemptedhomicides/petermiller.aspx|title=Norfolk Constabulary case review 2012|first=|last=|website=|accessdate=14 May 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120130185444/http://www.norfolk.police.uk/newsevents/coldcases/homicideattemptedhomicides/petermiller.aspx|archivedate=30 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> |- | 1985 || Sandra Phillips || [[Swansea]] || The mother of four was found beaten and strangled inside the sex shop she managed, which was locked up. Two brothers were wrongly convicted and spent seven years behind bars before their 1992 release, after which police apologised for investigational failings. Reviews of the case in 2002 and 2004 turned up new information but no killer, and in 2009 it was announced that the investigation would cease unless and until new information surfaced.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/south_west/8299042.stm Sex shop murder probe draws blank] – retrieved 10 October 2009 and published the day before</ref> |- | 1985 || [[Death of Keith Blakelock|PC Keith Blakelock]] || London || PC Blakelock was defending firefighters as they tended to a burning supermarket during the [[Broadwater Farm riot]]; he stumbled and was set upon by a mob with bladed weapons. Three men were convicted in 1987, but the convictions were overturned after forensic evidence suggested interview transcripts had been falsified. The officer in charge of the original investigation was cleared of inventing a statement by one of the accused.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/crime/9485277/Pc-Keith-Blakelock-murder-new-charge-after-27-years.html|title=Pc Keith Blakelock murder: new charge after 27 years|date=18 August 2012|website=Telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> |- | 6 November 1985 || Phil Nickson || [[Stoke Newington]], London || A 32-year-old civil servant killed by a blow to the head in Newington Green Road at about 5 pm on 6 November 1985. An extensive police investigation including a reconstruction on the BBC programme ''Crimewatch'' failed to solve the case. |- | 1986 ||[[Suzy Lamplugh]] || [[Fulham]], London || Suzy was a British estate agent reported missing on 28 July 1986 (aged 25) in Fulham, southwest London, England. She was officially declared dead, presumed murdered, in 1994. |- | 1986 || John William Malthouse || [[Cambridge]] || John Malthouse, of [[no fixed abode]], living in and around Cambridge for several years. On 22 August 1986 his body was found in toilets at Victoria Avenue, Midsummer Common, Cambridge. He had been the subject of an extremely violent assault.<ref name="CambsPolicePUB0211" /><ref>Cambridge Evening News (22 August 1986)</ref> |- | 1986 || [[Babes in the Wood murders (Wild Park)|Nicola Fellows & Karen Hadaway]] || [[Moulsecoomb]], north of Brighton || A local roofer, [[Russell Bishop (sex offender)|Russell Bishop]], was tried for the rape and strangulation of the two schoolgirls, but was acquitted. Bishop was convicted in 1991 for the kidnapping and attempted murder of a seven-year-old schoolgirl.<ref>{{cite news|first=Michael |last=Seamark |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1168245/Father-Babes-Wood-victim-arrested-suspicion-plotting-rape-murdered.html |title=Father of 'Babes in the Wood' victim arrested on suspicion of plotting to rape her before she was murdered &#124; Mail Online |publisher=Dailymail.co.uk |date= 8 April 2009|accessdate=21 August 2010 | location=London}}</ref> On 10 May 2016, a new suspect, who cannot be named for legal reasons, was arrested on suspicion of the murders.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/may/10/man-arrested-1986-babes-in-woods-murders-brighton Man arrested over 1986 'babes in the wood' murders in Brighton] ''[[The Guardian]]'', 10 May 2016. Retrieved 10 May 2016.</ref> On 2 February 2018 it was announced that Bishop would face trial for the murders at the Old Bailey; Bishop had pleaded not guilty the case is expected to start on 15 October 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-sussex-42919353|title=Man denies 1986 double child murder|date=2 February 2018|publisher=|accessdate=3 February 2018|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> |- | 1986 || Ann Ballantine || [[Edinburgh]]|| Ann was a 20-year-old woman that was found in a canal wrapped in carpet. She had been raped then throttled. The killer kept her before dumping her in the canal.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/unsolved-murder-files-that-stay-open-1-1348365|title=Unsolved murder files that stay open|publisher=''[[The Scotsman]]''|date=16 November 2007|accessdate=20 May 2013}}</ref> |- | 1986 || [[Murder of Linda Cook|Linda Cook]] || [[Portsmouth]] || A 24-year-old barmaid was raped and beaten to death in a school playground. Footprint evidence led to the conviction of an off duty sailor, Michael Shirley, and the case was dubbed the "Cinderella Murder". Shirley was sentenced to life in 1988, but eventually released in 2003 when DNA evidence proved he was not the killer.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/justice--but-at-what-cost-536404.html | work=The Independent | location=London | title=Justice – but at what cost? | first=Mark | last=Olden | date=19 August 2003 | accessdate=11 May 2010}}</ref> |- | 10 March 1987 || [[Daniel Morgan (private investigator)|Daniel Morgan]] || [[Sydenham]], [[Kent]] || Daniel Morgan was found with an axe wound to the head in the car park of the Golden Lion pub. There are suggestions [[police corruption]] is linked to his death.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jan/17/daniel-morgan-suspects-named-in-court-30-years-after-killing ''theguardian.com'']</ref> |- | 28 March 1987 || Helen Fleet || [[Weston-super-Mare]] || The brutal murder of Helen Fleet has left a lasting legacy in Weston-super-Mare. Many years since the frenzied attack, some townsfolk still fear returning to the beauty spot where she met her end. People continue to talk about the murder, apparently it was a motiveless attack on a defenceless pensioner.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gertlushonline.co.uk/1987-helen-fleet-murder.html |title=1987 Helen Fleet unsolved murder |publisher=Gertlushonline.co.uk |date=28 March 1987 |accessdate=21 August 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100813095211/http://www.gertlushonline.co.uk/1987-helen-fleet-murder.html |archivedate=13 August 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> |- | 1987 || [[Murder of Simon Dale|Simon Dale]] || [[Leintwardine]], [[Shropshire]] ||The body of Simon Dale, a near-blind recluse and former architect, was found at Heath House, an isolated 17th century mansion on the Shropshire/Herefordshire border. Dale's corpse bore the marks of a savage attack believed to have been inflicted some two days earlier. His ex-wife, the Baroness de Stempel (née Susan Wilberforce), stood trial in July 1989 for the murder of her former husband (earlier charges of murder against two of the Baroness's children, Marcus and Sophia Wilberforce, had been dropped); she was found not guilty. No one else has ever been charged with the murder. The investigation coincidentally revealed a fraud committed by the Baroness against her late aunt, Lady Illingworth. Police investigating the fraud made a search of the grounds of Heath House for missing gold bullion said to be worth some £10 million, but nothing was ever found.<ref>{{cite news| work=The Independent | location=London | title= Baroness de Stempel: How the death of an eccentric architect revealed a web of murder, fraud and intrigue | first=Terry | last=Kirby | date=4 August 2007 }}</ref> |- | 23 March 1988 || [[Murder of Deborah Linsley|Debbie Linsley]] || [[London Victoria|Victoria Station, London]] || Debbie Linsley, 26, from [[Bromley]] was found murdered in the carriage of a [[Network SouthEast]] train at Victoria station. She had died from multiple stab wounds to the heart. The case was reopened in 2002 but no-one has so far been arrested. She lived and worked in [[Edinburgh]] and had been visiting her parents and brother Gordon. She got on the 14:16 train in an old-fashioned compartment from [[Petts Wood railway station|Petts Wood]] to London Victoria stations. Screams were heard between [[Brixton railway station|Brixton]] and London Victoria. The killer left traces of his blood at the scene but the murder weapon, thought to be a knife with a blade length of between 13 and 19 centimetres, was not found. There is a £20,000 reward for information.<ref name ="BBC News 21_03_2013">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-ixtonengland-london-21875096|title=BBC News – Debbie Linsley murder: Reward offer over 1988 train death|website=BBC News|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> The case led to Network SouthEast reconfiguring the interiors of their trains and removing the compartments from most workings. |- | 20 April 1988 || Inga Maria Hauser || Ballypatrick Forest, near [[Ballycastle, County Antrim]], [[Northern Ireland]] ||Inga Maria Hauser, 19, a German tourist, was found murdered in the remote Ballypatrick Forest area of County Antrim, [[Northern Ireland]]. She was last seen on the [[Stranraer]] to [[Larne]] ferry two weeks before her body was discovered strangled and sexually assaulted. Police have been able to identify a possible DNA profile of the culprit to a number of nearby villages but have been unable to obtain enough evidence to charge any suspects.<ref>[https://m.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/police-close-the-net-on-killer-of-german-backpacker-inga-maria-hauser-28599578.html "Police close the net on killer of German backpacker Inga Maria Hauser"] Belfast Telegraph</ref> |- | 18 June 1988 || Marie Wilks || M50 motorway, near Bushley, Hereford & Worcester || Wilks, aged 22 and seven months pregnant, was driving the family's [[Morris Marina]] when the vehicle broke down on the M50 motorway. Leaving her 13-month-old son and 11-year-old sister in the car, Wilks walked approximately 700 yards along the hard shoulder to use the emergency telephone to call for help. At some point during the call, Wilks was abducted. She was found dead two days later, three miles from the location of the emergency phone (which had been found hanging down by its cord). Wilks had been stabbed in the neck. An artist's impression of the suspect resulted in the arrest and subsequent trial of soldier Eddie Browning, who spent five-and-a-half years in prison after being convicted of the murder in November 1989. He was ultimately released in May 1994 after the court of appeal ruled the conviction unsafe due to crucial evidence being withheld by the police. Browning received a £600,000 pay-out for wrongful imprisonment. In May 2018, Browning died aged 63. Reviews of the case have failed to uncover any other potential evidence or suspects.<ref name ="BBC News 24_09_2014">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/herefordandworcester/content/articles/2008/05/14/m50_marie_wilks_timeline_feature.shtml|title=BBC News - M50 murder - Timeline|accessdate=4 August 2018}}</ref><ref name ="BBC News 17_05_2018">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-44160580|title=BBC News - Marie Wilks murder: Wrongly convicted Eddie Browning dies|website=BBC News|accessdate=4 August 2018}}</ref> |- | 21 December 1988 || [[Lockerbie bombing]] || Scottish airspace || On 21 December 1988, Pan Am Flight 103 from Heathrow to New York exploded over the Scottish town of Lockerbie, killing all 259 people on board and 11 on the ground. In January 2001, Libyan [[Abdelbaset al-Megrahi]] was found guilty of mass murder and jailed for life with a minimum term of 20 years. However, no-one else has been brought to court, leaving the case open. <!-- Ask the police. They'll tell you the case officially remains under investigation. Or Robert Black QC, either he or Dr Jim Swire have asked the same thing. --> In August 2009, Megrahi was released from prison on compassionate grounds and returned to Libya due to advanced prostate cancer, from which he died in 2012. Some relatives of the dead welcomed the decision to release Megrahi, as they were convinced that he was wrongly convicted of the mass murder.<ref>Gall, Charlie. [http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/2009/08/21/lockerbie-megrahi-s-release-means-truth-of-who-was-behind-bombing-may-never-be-known-86908-21612920/ "Lockerbie: Megrahi's release means truth of who was behind bombing may never be known"]. ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]''. 21 August 2009</ref> |- | February 1989 || James Hassard || Caol, near Fort William || The badly beaten body of James "Jimmy" Hassard, 47, was found in a car park in the Highland village of Caol, near Fort William, in the early hours of Saturday, 18 February 1989. Mr Hassard had been drinking in the nearby Lochaber Bar between about 8{{nbsp}}pm on Friday, 17 February and 1{{nbsp}}am on Saturday. Despite a lengthy police inquiry, no-one has ever been caught. In 2010, Northern Constabulary said they are conducting a review into the murder in the hope that some new evidence may come to light and ultimately resolve the case.<ref>[http://www.northern.police.uk/News-and-Media/james-hassard-murder.htm/ "Northern Constabulary press announcement"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111124083549/http://www.northern.police.uk/News-and-Media/james-hassard-murder.htm |date=24 November 2011 }}.</ref> |}
==1990s== {| class="wikitable" |- ! width=5%| Year ! style="width:20%;"| Name of victim(s) ! style="width:15%;"| Location body found ! style="width:60%e;"| Notes |- | June 1990 || Leonard Gomm || Bletchingdon, [[Oxfordshire]] || Mr Gomm, 75, was a [[taxicab driver]] found stabbed to death in Hampton Gay, near Bletchingdon in Oxfordshire, at 10:50{{nbsp}}am on 13 June 1990. His [[Ford Granada (Europe)|Ford Granada]] taxi was found five yards away. Mr Gomm had radioed his employers four hours earlier (at about 6:35{{nbsp}}am) telling them he was taking a passenger to [[Bicester]]. Police believe he picked up the fare from [[Gloucester Green]], [[Oxford]]. Two witnesses saw the victim driving his taxi with a passenger at around this time. No money or valuables had been taken from Mr Gomm or his taxi leaving the motive as to his murder a mystery. On the 20th anniversary of the murder, [[Thames Valley Police]] reported the uncovering of new forensic evidence which could shed light on the motive.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10309353|work=BBC News|title='Crucial' evidence to 1990 Oxfordshire murder|date=14 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heart.co.uk/oxfordshire/news/local/new-clues-murder-inquiry/|title=New clues in murder inquiry|website=Heart Oxfordshire|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> |- | 3 August 1990 || Ann Heron || Aeolian House, [[Darlington]] || The mother-of-three had her throat slit while sunbathing outside her family home. Her husband, Peter, found the body and was later charged with her murder but the case collapsed. Nobody else has been charged with the murder.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/crime/8308225.Continued_appeal_over_20_year_unsolved_murder/ |title=Murder of Ann Heron still unsolved | date=2010-08-03 |accessdate=2018-01-28 |publisher=The Northern Echo}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/news/13620230._I_met_the_man_who_claimed_to_be_Ann_Heron_s_murderer__says_retired_shopworker/ |title=I met the man who claimed to be Ann Heron's murderer |date=2015-08-22 |accessdate=2018-01-28 |publisher=York Press}}</ref> |- | December 1990 || Steven Johnson || [[Mow Cop]], Staffordshire || On 22 December, insurance salesman and part-time taxi driver Johnson was last sighted at 3:30{{nbsp}}am collecting a fare in [[Hanley, Staffordshire|Hanley]] bound for Packmoor. His body was discovered by a [[dog walking|dog walker]] four hours later with his throat cut 20 yards from his taxi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/news/Police-look-Mow-Cop-murderer/article-3030366-detail/article.html|title=Hunt goes on for killer of Steven Johnson|website=Stoke Sentinel|accessdate=20 December 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101225160526/http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/news/Police-look-Mow-Cop-murderer/article-3030366-detail/article.html|archivedate=25 December 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> |- | 1991 || [[Murder of Penny Bell|Penny Bell]] || [[Perivale]], London || Body found in a car in Gurnell Grove Leisure Centre car park. The victim was a 43-year-old [[businesswoman]] and mother of two, who was stabbed 50 times as she sat behind the wheel of her car.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/4218936.stm|title=BBC NEWS – UK – England – London – Reward in mother murder mystery|publisher=|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> |- 1991 || Nicola Payne || [[Coventry]], [[West Midlands]] || | 1991 || Lynne Trenholm || [[Boughton, Cheshire|Boughton]], [[Chester]] || Trenholm was found dead in Pinky's massage parlour in Boughton, Chester, on 9 June 1991. She had been stabbed multiple times. Despite there being a solid fingerprint recovered from the scene, the police have no suspects and appeals are still made in an effort to solve Trenholm's murder.<ref>{{cite news|title=Help us catch Lynne's brutal killer|url=http://www.chesterstandard.co.uk/news/113701/help-us-catch-lynne-s-brutal-killer.aspx|accessdate=19 January 2017|work=Chester First|date=22 June 2012|language=en}}</ref> |- | 1991 || Sandy Drummond || [[Fife]], Scotland || Reclusive Drummond, 33, was found dead on a farm track close to the home he shared with his brother, an isolated cottage in St Andrews, Fife, on 24 June 1991. Just days prior to his death, Drummond had withdrawn large amounts of cash from his accounts, although the money was later found in the house. He had also resigned from his job three days before his death. On the day itself, he was seen running from his house to fields opposite carrying a blue sports bag which has never been found. At 2:30{{nbsp}}pm, a man was seen on a bus near to Drummond's cottage with a blood stained bandage wrapped around his hand. This man was never traced. Several occasions before Drummond's death (and twice on the actual day), an orange [[Morris Marina]] was seen parked outside the cottage, but it is still unknown who owned this car or who visited him. Drummond's death was originally ruled as natural, but forensics later revealed he had injuries to his neck.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fifetoday.co.uk/news/local-headlines/tv_appeal_over_murder_mystery_1_164189|title=TV APPEAL OVER MURDER MYSTERY|publisher=|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> |- | 1991 ||[[The Bolney Torso]]||[[Bolney]], [[Sussex]] || In October 1991 a body was discovered in woodland off Broxmead Lane in Bolney, Sussex. The head and hands had been removed and the victim was never identified. In March 2009 police exhumed the body and gave a revised description of the victim. He was between 5&nbsp;ft 6 and 5&nbsp;ft 8 tall, well built and aged 35 - 45. Police issued pictures of his clothing, including a light-blue shirt, with a distinctive motif on its pocket.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hastingsobserver.co.uk/mid-sussex-news/Video-New-information-about-the.5114848.jp |title=Video: New information about the Bolney torso |publisher=Hastings Observer |date= |accessdate=21 August 2010}}</ref> |- | 1991 || Nicola Payne || [[Coventry]], [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]] || Nicola Payne, aged 18, went missing from the Wood End area on 14 December 1991. She was on her way to her parents' house from her home in Winston Avenue. She had a six-month-old son at the time of her disappearance. In June 2012 police began a search of parkland after being given new information.<ref name = "BBC2012-06-19">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-coventry-warwickshire-18501540|title=BBC News – Nicola Payne: Police search Coventry parkland|website=BBC News|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> On 20 June 2012, Nigel Barwell and his brother-in-law Thomas O'Reilly were arrested by the police<ref name="BBC2012-06-20">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-coventry-warwickshire-18516902|title=BBC News – Nicola Payne: Two arrests in missing mum search|website=BBC News|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> but later released.<ref name ="ITN22June12">{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/central/2012-06-22/nicola-paynes-father-tells-of-sadness-and-disappointment/|title=Nicola Payne's father tells of sadness and disappointment|website=ITV News|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> On 27 January 2015, Barwell and O'Reilly were charged with her murder.<ref name="BBC27Jan2015">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-coventry-warwickshire-31006969|title=Nicola Payne death: Two charged with 1991 murder and abduction|website=BBC News|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> However, on 16 November 2015, Barwell and O'Reilly were found not guilty of murdering Payne<ref name="BBC16Nov2015">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-34832136 |title=Two cleared of Coventry mother Nicola Payne's 1991 murder|website=BBC News|accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref> A tent which appeared to show [[DNA]] evidence against the defendants had been stored in uncertain conditions for a month and cross contamination was possible.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/nov/16/two-men-cleared-of-nicola-payne-murder|title=Two men cleared of Nicola Payne murder|first=Steven|last=Morris|date=16 November 2015|publisher=|accessdate=1 October 2016|via=The Guardian}}</ref> |- | October 1992 || Nikki Allan || [[Sunderland, Tyne and Wear|Sunderland]] || Seven-year-old Nikki Allan was battered to death in the then derelict Exchange Building. George Heron, 24, a neighbour was subsequently charged with the murder. However at his trial the case collapsed as it was deemed that his confession had been gained by coercion. In 2006 police confirmed that the Nikki Allan murder was being reinvestigated by a "cold case" review team based at Northumbria police headquarters.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2006/oct/11/ukcrime.features11 | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=There will be no peace for me | first=Julie | last=Bindel | date=11 October 2006 | accessdate=25 January 2012}}</ref> In September 2013, BBC's Crimewatch reconstructed a second appeal in an attempt to solve the case.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tyne-24056902 | work=BBC News | title=Nikki Allan murder: Crimewatch appeal over 1992 killing | date=12 September 2013}}</ref> |- | November 1992 || Natalie Pearman || [[Norwich]], Norfolk || 16-year-old Natalie was strangled and her body dumped in woodland at Ringland Hills, on the edge of Norwich. At around 3:45{{nbsp}}am on 20 November, a lorry driver taking a short cut through Ringland Hills spotted Natalie's body in a layby.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edp24.co.uk/Content/Features/Unsolved/Unsolved1.asp |title=Norfolk Lifestyle |publisher=EDP24 |date= |accessdate=21 August 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090302223549/http://edp24.co.uk/Content/Features/Unsolved/Unsolved1.asp |archivedate=2 March 2009 }}</ref> New information about the case were received in November 2012.<ref name = "BBC2012-11-29">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-norfolk-20538523|title=BBC News – Natalie Pearman: New hope over 1992 Norwich murder|website=BBC News|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> |- | December 1992 || Johanna Young || [[Watton, Norfolk]] || On 23 December, 14-year-old Johanna left her home in Merton Road, Watton, at around 7:30{{nbsp}}pm and was seen outside her local fish and chip shop half an hour later. The alarm was raised the following morning when she failed to turn up for her paper round and, on Boxing Day, her body was found in a freezing pond near her home and clothes and shoes discarded nearby.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/postcard-may-hold-clue-to-girls-death-1476011.html | work=The Independent | location=London | title=Postcard may hold clue to girl's death | first=Terry | last=Kirby | date=2 January 1993 | accessdate=11 May 2010}}</ref> |- | 21 January 1993 || Arthur Brumhill || [[Northampton]], Northamptonshire || 76-year-old Arthur Brumhill's body was found in the basement of the pet and garden centre on Wellingborough Road, where he worked part-time by a fellow employee. He had died from several blows to the head caused by a blunt metal object, thought to be a [[Tire iron|tyre iron]] missing from the scene. The killer is suspected to have escaped out of an upstairs window with a small amount of money taken. An eyewitness described seeing Arthur with another man in his teens with "mousey-brown" hair, standing at about 5&nbsp;ft 5in tall, in the shop the evening of the murder. Despite the case appearing on [[Crimewatch]] and several arrests being made the case remains unsolved to this day. On 21 January 2013, the 20th anniversary of the murder, police announced they were reviewing the case and hoped that advances in Forensic Analysis and DNA profiling could bring the killer to justice.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-northamptonshire-21145758 | work=BBC News | title=Arthur Brumhill murder: Forensics hope in pet shop killing | date=22 January 2013 | accessdate=14 April 2013}}</ref> |- | 1993 || Doris Shelley || [[Martlesham]], Suffolk || Pensioner Doris Shelley died after she was attacked in her own home at Martlesham, near Woodbridge on 11 February 1993.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.suffolk.police.uk/News+And+Appeals/Unsolved+Cases/Murder+Doris+Shelley.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060929101959/http://www.suffolk.police.uk/News+And+Appeals/Unsolved+Cases/Murder+Doris+Shelley.htm |dead-url=yes |archive-date=29 September 2006 |title=Murder – Doris Shelley |publisher=Suffolk.police.uk |date=11 February 1993 |accessdate=21 August 2010 }}</ref> |- | 1993 || Jean Bradley || [[Acton, London|Acton]], London || Stabbed to death in Carbery Avenue. Victim was a 47-year-old businesswoman. A man was charged, but due to a lack of evidence the case was dropped.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/feb/16/ukcrime.foodanddrink | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=Gone but not forgotten | first=Jay | last=Rayner | date=16 February 2003 | accessdate=11 May 2010}}</ref> |- | 1993 || Harry and Megan Tooze || [[Llanharry]], [[South Wales]] || Shot at point blank range in their home at Ty Ar y Waun Farm. Jonathan Jones, the boyfriend of their daughter Cheryl was convicted of their murder, but the verdict was quickly overturned on appeal. Since then [[South Wales Police]] have made several attempts to solve the murder, but no further arrests have been made.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tooze murders: Call to publish murder review findings|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-south-east-wales-23459713|accessdate=6 January 2017|work=BBC News|date=26 July 2013}}</ref> |- | 1993 || Karen Hales || [[Ipswich]], Suffolk || 21-year-old Karen Hales was murdered in her own home in front of her young daughter. She had been stabbed and her body set on fire during a vicious attack on Sunday 21 November.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.suffolk.police.uk/News+And+Appeals/Unsolved+Cases/Murder+Karen+Hales.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060929102009/http://www.suffolk.police.uk/News+And+Appeals/Unsolved+Cases/Murder+Karen+Hales.htm |dead-url=yes |archive-date=29 September 2006 |title=Murder – Karen Hales |publisher=Suffolk.police.uk |date=21 November 1993 |accessdate=21 August 2010 }}</ref> |- | 1994 || Chris Little || [[Stockport]] || Shot while driving his car. Arran Coghlan was charged but cleared; the next decade Coghlan went on to be charged and cleared in two other murders and with cocaine smuggling.<ref name="Coghlan">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-13728936 Cheshire businessman Arran Coghlan cleared in drugs case] – 10 June 2011 – Accessed 10 June 2011.</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/bullets-halt-the-rise-of-a-northern-gangster-1415880.html| work=Independent | title=Bullets halt the rise of a northern gangster | first=Peter| last=Victor| date=24 July 1994| location=London}}</ref> |- | 1994 || [[Murder of Lindsay Rimer|Lindsay Rimer]]|| [[Hebden Bridge]], West Yorkshire || Teenager Lindsay Jo Rimer lived with her parents at Cambridge Street, Hebden Bridge. She was a pupil at Calder High School. At around 10{{nbsp}}pm on 7 November 1994 she left home to visit the local Spar Supermarket in Crown Street, Hebden Bridge, to buy cornflakes. On the way to the shop she visited the Trades Club in Holme Street. According to CCTV footage in the supermarket Lindsay paid for the cornflakes at 10:22{{nbsp}}pm. Five months later on 12 April 1995, her body was recovered from the Rochdale Canal, approximately one mile upstream from Hebden Bridge town centre.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lindsay Rimer death: Man held over 1990s canal body find|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-37914713|accessdate=6 January 2017|work=BBC News|date=8 November 2016}}</ref> |- | 1994 || Rikki Neave || Peterborough || Six-year-old Rikki's naked body was found in woodland near his home. He had been strangled. Rikki was last seen leaving his Welland estate home on 28 November 1994. His mother Ruth was convicted of child neglect and also initially charged with murder, but was cleared of the murder charge at court in 1996.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Franklin |first1=Neil |title=RIKKI NEAVE: Sensational trial hears of black magic, beatings and drug-dealing|url=https://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/news/environment/rikki-neave-sensational-trial-hears-of-black-magic-beatings-and-drug-dealing-1-152807 |agency=Peterborough Telegraph |date=24 November 2004}}</ref> A man was arrested in April 2016 for his murder following a renewed investigation into the case in 2015, but police later confirmed he would not face charges.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rikki Neave death: No charges over schoolboy murder |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cambridgeshire-44563929 |agency=BBC News |date=21 June 2018}}</ref> |- | 1994 || Dr Michael Meenaghan (Spike)|| [[Blackbird Leys]], [[Oxford]] || A lecturer at the Sir William Dunn School of Pathology at Oxford University, Dr Meenaghan, 35, was shot at about 4:30{{nbsp}}pm at his end-terrace home on the Blackbird Leys estate in Oxford. Police called it an apparently motiveless attack. He was shot through the kitchen window of his home at 4:30{{nbsp}}pm on 10 December by person or persons unknown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/hitman-theory-after-oxford-lecturer-shot-1387195.html|title=Hitman theory after Oxford lecturer shot|website=The Independent|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> |- | 1994 || Tracy Mertens || Eaton, [[Macclesfield]], Cheshire || Aged 31, from Rochdale, Greater Manchester, died 24 hours after being left on the steps of a church by her killers, who abducted her when she returned to pick up belongings from her former home in [[Nechells]], [[Birmingham]]. She suffered horrific burns and was found by a man who heard her cries as he walked past the churchyard on 23 December 1994. It was a bi