k with Mr Wood. As the victim approached the front door he was shot in the neck with a sawn off shotgun. Mr Wood bled to death at the scene on the Racecourse Estate. The suspect, described as white, aged between 25-35, 5'7 in height, of slim build, with sharp facial features and wearing an unzipped dark-coloured anorak, was seen to run into Kempton Avenue. On the 15th anniversary of the murder, detectives offered a £20,000 reward for information leading to the identification, arrest and prosecution of the person responsible.<ref name ="Mirror 21_01_2013">{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/robin-wood-new-police-probe-1531417|title=Robin Wood: New police probe into dad's doorstep shooting in 1998|author=Justin Penrose|date=13 January 2013|website=mirror|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> |- | 1998 || Julia Webb || Sandiway near [[Northwich]], Cheshire || Housewife Julia Webb, 52, was battered with a blunt instrument while walking her dog near her home in Sandiway on 22 July 1998.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.warringtonguardian.co.uk/news/5311090.THE_brutal_murder_of_Sandiway_mum_Julia_Webb_is_to_be_recreated_by_actors_for_the_BBC_s_Crimewatch_p/ |title=The brutal murder of Sandiway mum Julia Webb is to be recreated by actors for the BBC's Crimewatch p[rogramme] |work=[[Warrington Guardian]] |date= 3 September 1998|accessdate=1 January 2018 }}</ref> |- | 1998 || Lyn Bryant || [[Truro]], [[Cornwall]] || Lyn Bryant was murdered as she was walking her dog along a country lane at Ruan High Lanes near Truro in Cornwall on 20 October 1998. Her body was found at 2:40{{nbsp}}pm. She had been stabbed several times. Bryant's killing is said to be linked to the murder of schoolgirl Kate Bushell the previous year.<ref name ="BBC News 13_10_2008">{{cite web|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cornwall/7666855.stm|title=BBC News - Family plea over dog walk murder|website=BBC News|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref> |- | 1998 || Saul "Solly" Nahome || [[Finchley]], London || Nahome was shot at his home several times in the back; upon collapsing, he was shot again in the head. The case is believed to be linked to the disappearance earlier in 1998 of business associate [[Gilbert Wynter]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-13490753 Met police bid to solve murder in Finchley] – 20 May 2011 – Accessed 10 June 2011</ref> |- | 1999 || Steven Brown || Tranent, [[Edinburgh]] || The beaten and stabbed body of Steven Brown was found in Tranent, on the outskirts of Edinburgh on 21 February 1999. Nobody has ever been arrested for the murder.<ref name ="BBC News 17_01_2013">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-21058843|title=BBC News - New probe into 1999 murder of Steven Brown in Tranent|website=BBC News|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref> |- | 1999 || [[Jill Dando]] || Fulham, London || On the morning of 26 April 1999, Dando left the home of her fiancé, Dr. Alan Farthing, and returned to her house in Gowan Avenue, Fulham, West London. As she reached her front door at about 11:30{{nbsp}}am, she was shot once in the head.<ref>{{cite news | publisher = BBC News | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/328804.stm | title = BBC presenter shot dead | date = 26 April 1999 }}</ref> Her body was discovered shortly afterwards by a friend, local resident Helen Doble, and she was taken to the nearby [[Charing Cross Hospital]] where she was declared [[dead on arrival]] at 1:03{{nbsp}}pm [[British Summer Time|BST]]. After a huge amount of press coverage and a 13-month investigation police arrested [[Barry George]], a convicted sex offender, for her murder. Originally convicted on 2 July 2001 to [[life imprisonment]] George appealed the conviction in November 2007. Following an eight-week hearing he was acquitted on 1 August 2008.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7536815.stm | title= George not guilty of Dando murder | publisher= BBC News | date= 1 August 2008 | accessdate= 1 August 2008}}</ref> |- | 1999 || Mary Lazenby || [[Bethnal Green]] || Aged 80 and {{convert|4|ft|8|in}} tall, Lazenby was murdered on 22 May 1999 at her flat at Rochester Court, Wilmott Street, [[Bethnal Green]]. Her killer was possibly a man posing as a water board official. Lazenby was disabled, after a motorcycle accident had caused the loss of her left foot. Once a successful restaurateur in [[South Shields]] and known as the 'Curry Queen of South Shields', she had eventually lost her business and settled in Bethnal Green with her son and grandchildren.<ref>{{cite news|title=Murder Reward is Doubled|newspaper=Shields Gazette|url=http://www.shieldsgazette.com/news/local-news/murder-reward-is-doubled-1-1254336|date=2 June 2000}}</ref> |- | 1999 || David Scott || London || Scott, 30, was stabbed to death in a Tottenham underpass. In 2012 prosecutors dropped a case against Kwame Appiah for the murder on the basis of scientific evidence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tottenhamjournal.co.uk/news/crime-court/man_cleared_of_1999_tottenham_murder_1_1447649|title=Man cleared of 1999 Tottenham murder|author=Court Reporter|website=Tottenham Journal|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> |- | 1999 || Vicky Hall || [[Trimley St Mary]], Suffolk || Seventeen-year-old Victoria (Vicky) Hall went missing at about 2:30{{nbsp}}am on Sunday, 19 September 1999, as she walked towards her home in Faulkeners Way, Trimley St Mary. Vicky's body was found, about 25 miles away, in a stream near Creeting St Peter (near Stowmarket) at 7:30{{nbsp}}pm on Friday, 24 September 1999.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.suffolk.police.uk/News+And+Appeals/Unsolved+Cases/Murder+Vicky+Hall.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060929102020/http://www.suffolk.police.uk/News+And+Appeals/Unsolved+Cases/Murder+Vicky+Hall.htm |dead-url=yes |archive-date=29 September 2006 |title=Murder – Vicky Hall |publisher=Suffolk.police.uk |date= |accessdate=21 August 2010 }}</ref> |- | 1999 || David Barnshaw || Stockport || The 32-year-old drug dealer was abducted and forced to drink petrol. He died in a burning car on 20 September 1999. Arran Coghlan – previously cleared of the murder of Chris Little – was prosecuted but cleared after it emerged the prosecution held undisclosed evidence concerning another possible suspect. Coghlan went on to be charged and cleared with a third count of murder and cocaine smuggling.<ref name="Coghlan"/> |- | 1999 ||John Nisbett and William Lindsay || [[Haddington, East Lothian|Haddington]], [[East Lothian]] || The bodies of drug dealers John Nisbett of Craigneuk and William Lindsay of Motherwell were found on the outskirts of Haddington. It is thought they had been abducted, stabbed and shot, with their bodies then set on fire. It is said to be the outcome of a Glasgow drug war. No arrests have been made in connection with the case.<ref name ="BBC News 15_10_1999">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/474219.stm|title=BBC News - UK: Scotland New lead in 'drugs dispute' murder|website=BBC News|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref> |}
== 2000s ==
{| class="wikitable" |- ! width=5%| Year ! style="width:20%;"| Name of victim(s) ! style="width:15%;"| Location body found ! style="width:60%;"| Notes |- | 2000 || [[Frank McPhee]] || [[Maryhill]], [[Glasgow]] || McPhie, himself twice cleared of murder, was shot by a sniper in a block of flats opposite his own as he returned home.<ref>[http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/crime-courts/police-renew-investigation-into-murder-of-gangland-boss.23360398 Police renew investigation into murder of gangland boss] 6 February 2014 – Accessed 6 February 2014</ref> |- | 2001 || Unknown boy || [[River Thames]] || "[[Adam (unsolved Thames murder case)|Torso in the Thames]]" victim |- | 5 November 2001 || Michaela Hague || Spitalfields, [[Sheffield]] || Michaela Hague was a 25-year-old woman working as a prostitute. She was stabbed 19 times and her body dumped on wasteland at Spitalfields, near Sheffield City centre. She managed to give a description of her attacker as she lay dying in the arms of a police officer. She said her attacker was white and clean shaven with fair hair. He was wearing a wedding ring and drove a blue Ford Sierra car with a roof rack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/south_yorkshire/6122522.stm|title=BBC NEWS – UK – England – South Yorkshire – Fresh leads in prostitute murder|publisher=|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> |- | 13 March 2002 || {{anchor|Exmoor Body in the Bag|Winsford Hill John Doe|Body in the Bag}}Exmoor Body in the Bag || Winsford Hill, [[Winsford, Somerset]] || The man's badly decomposed corpse was found on 13 March 2002 wrapped in bin bags, a green single bed sheet and a single duvet. He had been tied with a stereo wire that was found with the remains. He is thought to have died 2–3 years before being found. It is not clear if the body had been brought into the UK from abroad. In May 2002, Detectives appealed on Crimewatch UK in the hope someone would recognise him but nobody called in to say who he was. In September, a new reconstruction of the man's head was released in a fresh appeal to identify him. He was 25–35 years old with black or dark brown hair and 5&nbsp;ft 8–5&nbsp;ft 9ins tall. He was thought to be Mediterranean, Middle Eastern or North African. He was wearing a gold chain that had a 22-carat pendant with the verse 225 from the Koran, the Holy Text of Islam, inscribed in Arabic across it. In September 2006 a funeral was held for the mystery victim.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.somersetcountygazette.co.uk/news/920591.mystery_body_to_be_laid_to_rest/ |title=Mystery body to be laid to rest |first=Chris |last=Alder |publisher=Somerset County Gazette|website=somersetcountygazette.co.uk |date=17 September 2006 |accessdate=13 October 2011}}</ref> |- | 28 March 2002 || Michelle Bettles || Norwich, Norfolk || Mother of three small children, none of whom were in her care, Michelle was last seen alive in the Queens Road area of Norwich. Her fully clothed body was found in a woodland off Podmore Lane, Scarning, three days later.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/norfolk/6179999.stm | work=BBC News | title=Man's fears over daughter's death | date=14 December 2006 | accessdate=11 May 2010}}</ref> In June 2012 criminologist [[David Wilson (criminologist)|Professor David Wilson]] suggested that the killer was serial killer [[Steve Wright (serial killer)|Steve Wright]], but police dismissed the theory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eveningnews24.co.uk/news/police_dismiss_theory_that_suffolk_strangler_steve_wright_could_be_linked_to_murder_of_norwich_prostitute_1_1407205|title=Police dismiss theory that Suffolk Strangler Steve Wright could be linked to murder of Norwich prostitute|website=Norwich Evening News|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> |- | 25 June 2002 || Alex Blue || [[Dowanhill]], [[Glasgow]] || A businessman from the city's west end, Blue was found outside his home with head injuries. He died two days later.<ref>[http://www.strathclyde.police.uk/whats_happening/feature_cases/murder_of_alexander_blue/ Murder of Alexander Blue] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120901023007/http://www.strathclyde.police.uk/whats_happening/feature_cases/murder_of_alexander_blue/ |date=1 September 2012 }} ([[Strathclyde Police]])</ref> Blue ran a taxi business with an annual turnover of £7m. One theory is that he was the victim of a house buying scam. He told friends he was in the process of buying a new house and planned to view it the day after he was attacked. It was later discovered the home had never been on the market. Although nobody has been charged with the murder, Blue's mother and brother are convinced they know who murdered him. His brother said: "I know who was behind this but they got someone else to carry out their dirty work for them."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/news/scottishnews/4118577/I-want-bloody-revenge-for-the-death-of-my-son.html|title=I want bloody revenge for the death of my son|publisher=''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]''|last=Nelson|first=Irena|date=9 February 2012|accessdate=20 May 2013|location=London}}</ref> |- | October 2002 || Julie Dorsett || [[Walthamstow]] || Dorsett, a 33-year-old prostitute, vanished in 2002 and her skull and upper body were discovered buried in an allotment in 2008. It is believed her remains were placed there shortly after she disappeared. In 2012 her former partner, Sinclair Lewis, was cleared of killing her and of burying her body.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian-series.co.uk/news/9838993.WALTHAMSTOW__Man_cleared_of_allotment_body_murder/|title=WALTHAMSTOW: Man cleared of allotment body murder|author=Daniel Binns|website=East London and West Essex Guardian Series|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> |- | 8 October 2002 || Billy Sibbald || [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1]], near [[Musselburgh]] || Father of three Billy Sibbald went missing on 8 October 2002 from [[Joppa, Edinburgh]], after telling his wife he was meeting business associates. Three months later, his [[decomposing]] body was found in woodland by a lay-by on the [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1]] near [[Musselburgh]]. There have been various theories for Billy Sibbalds murder including one that he may have been the victim of a [[gangland killing]].<ref name="Sibbald">{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/photo_hope_in_hunt_for_landlord_s_killer_1_873942|title=Photo hope in hunt for landlord's killer – News – Scotsman.com|date=26 March 2003|work=[[The Scotsman]]|publisher=[[Johnston Press]]|accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref> Due to a lack of information coming through to the police, nobody has been arrested for his murder.<ref name="Unsolved murders">{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/unsolved_murder_files_that_stay_open_1_1348365|title=Unsolved murder files that stay open – News – Scotsman.com|date=16 November 2007|work=[[The Scotsman]]|publisher=[[Johnston Press]]|accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref> |- | 3 February 2003 || Margaret Muller || Victoria Park, London || Muller, 27, was fatally stabbed while jogging in the park. Police suspect she may have been targeted in a robbery gone wrong.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-12351391|title=Victoria Park murder: Reward over Margaret Muller death|work=BBC News Online | date=3 February 2011 |accessdate =3 February 2011}}</ref> |- | 4 February 2003 |||Paul Savage || [[Mold, Flintshire|Mold]], [[Wales]] || 30-year-old postman who died after being attacked by two men while on his round in Mold, Flintshire. He had been struck on the head several times with a wooden baton and was found lying in a pool of blood on the driveway of the home of Flintshire councillor Ray Dodd. The police later said they knew why Savage was killed, but would not elaborate. There is a £100,000 reward for information.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/north_east/8498037.stm |title=BBC News – Mold postman murder appeal renewed seven years on |first= |last=|work=[[BBC News]] |date=4 February 2010 |publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] |location=[[London, England|London]]|accessdate=13 October 2011}}</ref> |- | 2003 || Peter Stone || [[Cottenham]], Cambridgeshire || Postman Peter Stone of Cottenham, a father of two, was attacked near the Chequers pub where he had been drinking on a Saturday night. He was found with serious head injuries in the early hours of the following morning. Stone was taken to Addenbrooke's hospital where he died.<ref name="CambsPolicePUB0211" /> |- | November 2004 || Alistair Wilson || [[Nairn]] || Alistair Wilson, 30, was shot dead on the doorstep of his home in Nairn near Inverness in November 2004. He was shot in the head at his home in Crescent Road one Sunday evening after his wife opened their door to the killer. Police have stated there appears absolutely no motive for the murder.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/one-year-on-who-killed-alistair-wilson-517368.html | work=The Independent | location=London | title=One year on, who killed Alistair Wilson? | date=29 November 2005 | accessdate=11 May 2010}}</ref> Detectives remain puzzled as to some of the peculiarities of the crime. The killer had asked for Wilson by name, and then handed an envelope to Wilson, who took it back inside briefly before returning to the door where he was gunned down; it is unknown what was inside as the killer took it with him when he fled. Police revealed that the gun that killed Wilson was a rare 1920s pistol; often referred to as a "ladies" gun, which was manufactured in [[Suhl]], [[Germany]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/scottish-news/top-stories/1920s-east-german-pistol-used-in-nairn-killing-1-707687|title=1920s East German pistol used in Nairn killing|publisher=''[[The Scotsman]]''|date=13 April 2005|accessdate=20 May 2013}}</ref> |- | 2005 || [[Murder of Robert McCartney|Robert McCartney]] || [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]] || Robert McCartney, 33, was killed during an altercation in Magennis' Bar. He was dragged outside onto Verner Street in the centre of the city and beaten and stabbed. Allegations were made, particularly by friends and relatives of McCartney, that there was involvement of the [[Provisional IRA|IRA]] and [[Sinn Féin]] in both the murder and subsequent cover-up.{{Citation needed|date=January 2016}} McCartney died of his wounds the following morning. |- | March 2006 || Carlton Alveranga and Richard Austin || [[Salford, Greater Manchester|Salford]] || The pair had been hired as [[hitman|hitmen]] to murder David Totton, and entered the Brass Handles [[public house]] to carry out their contract. Although Totton was shot, he survived. His assailants were then disarmed by the bar's patrons and shot dead with their own guns by a person or persons unknown. Alveranga and Austin's hirers were convicted of conspiracy to murder in 2007, but the actual killer or killers remain unidentified.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/6475601.stm | work=BBC News | title=Two guilty of pub execution plot | date=21 March 2007 | accessdate=11 May 2010}}</ref> |- | July 2006 || Jim Stanton || [[Liverpool]] || Stanton, a used car salesman, was shutting up shop after working late one Monday evening in July 2006, when at around 6{{nbsp}}pm, two armed men burst into the car showroom where he worked and opened fire. Although Stanton's colleagues managed to escape to safety, Stanton was stuck behind his desk which was situated just metres from the back wall of the showroom, which subsequently resulted in him receiving a number of fatal shots. The person(s) responsible have never been traced, although police have suggested that they suspect Stanton was not the intended target of the attack. A £20,000 reward has been offered by Merseyside police.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/profiles/18jgBj7M7kFBtg86bBtCyy3/jim-stanton-murder|title=05/09/2016, Crimewatch – Jim Stanton Murder – BBC One|website=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref> |- | September 2006 ||Jessie James || [[Moss Side]], [[Manchester]] || James was murdered in a drive by shooting in September 2006. It is believed his murder was a case of mistaken identity. Police have been worried about the lack of witnesses coming forward, possibly due to fear of the repercussions.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/death-in-moss-side-who-killed-jessie-james-925583.html | work=[[The Independent]] | location=London | title=Death in Moss Side: Who killed Jessie James? | date=11 September 2008 | accessdate=22 April 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308094713/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/death-in-moss-side-who-killed-jessie-james-925583.html|archivedate=8 March 2009}}</ref> |- | February 2007 || James Andre Smartt-Ford || London || On 3 February at 10:55{{nbsp}}pm the [[Metropolitan Police]] received a call of a shooting at an ice rink, where around 300 were attending a disco. A youth had shot 17-year-old Smartt-Ford, who had staggered down stairs to the ice and collapsed. He died at midnight in hospital. Although there were multiple witnesses, the killer has not been identified.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ukpress/article/ALeqM5jPgcneFaVMKj7TWfqIIG-RYLOhVA?docId=B28128191296717157A00|work=The Press Association|title=New appeal over ice rink murder|date=3 February 2011|accessdate=3 February 2011}}</ref> |- | 2008 || [[Murder of Andrew Cunningham|Andrew Cunningham]] || [[Earlsfield]], London || Andrew Cunningham, a 52-year-old convicted paedophile, was found stabbed with his genital mutilated in his caravan outside a haulage yard where he worked. Despite 500 witness statements and a £20,000 reward, no trace of the killer has been found. Police believe it was either a vigilante killing or a robbery.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hughes|first1=Mark|title=The murder nobody wants to help solve|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/the-murder-nobody-wants-to-help-solve-1726198.html|accessdate=6 January 2017|work=The Independent|date=1 July 2009}}</ref> |- | June 2009 || Anthony Otton || [[Fulham]], London || Otton, age 28, was killed by a single bullet through his heart just before 7{{nbsp}}pm on 4 June 2009, as he left Geranium House, in Fulham Court, London. On the day of a wake for Darcy Bruce, who was gunned down outside Wandsworth Prison on 1 May, officers from the Metropolitan Police Homicide and Serious Crime Command offered a £20,000 reward for information leading to the killers' prosecution. Family members believe he was the victim of revenge shooting.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Harding|first1=Eleanor|title=Three men arrested after 'revenge' shooting following prison murder|url=http://www.wandsworthguardian.co.uk/news/4441536.Three_men_arrested_after__revenge__shooting_following_prison_murder/|accessdate=6 January 2017|work=Wandsworth Guardian|date=16 June 2009}}</ref> |- | 2009 || [[Paula Hounslea]] || [[Fazakerley]], [[Liverpool]] || Paula Hounslea was a British victim of an unsolved murder. She had been missing since 22 August 2009 and her body was later found in a fire pit on the loop line cycle path in Fazakerley Liverpool on 5 May 2010 by a dog walker, the body was identified using Hounslea's medical and dental records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/2012/05/19/police-start-to-piece-together-last-movements-of-murdered-mum-paula-hounslea-100252-31002328/|title=Police start to piece together last movements of murdered mum Paula Hounslea|author=liverpoolecho Administrator|date=19 May 2012|website=liverpoolecho|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> |- | October 2009 || Alan Wood || [[Lound, Lincolnshire|Lound]], [[Lincolnshire]] || In October 2009, 50-year-old Wood was found dead in his home, tortured – possibly for financial details – and with head wounds and a slit throat. A £60,000 reward and televised appeals have not resulted in a prosecution.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-lincolnshire-12514225 Alan Wood murder has second appeal on BBC's Crimewatch] – 19 February 2011 – Accessed 19 February 2011</ref> |}
== 2010s ==
